{"title_page": "Education in Scotland", "text_new": "{{distinguish|Education Scotland}}\n{{refimprove|date=January 2019}}\n{{EngvarB|date=September 2015}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2015}}\n{{Infobox education in country\n|country name = Scotland\n|agency image = File:Scottish Government Logo.svg\n|agency = [[Education and Lifelong Learning Directorate|Scottish Government]]\n|leader titles = [[Cabinet Secretary for Education and Skills]] <br/> [[Minister for Children and Young People]] <br/> [[Minister for Further Education, Higher Education and Science]] \n|leader names = [[John Swinney]] [[Member of the Scottish Parliament|MSP]] <br/> [[Maree Todd]] [[Member of the Scottish Parliament|MSP]] <br/> [[Richard Lochhead]] [[Member of the Scottish Parliament|MSP]]\n|budget = \u00a32.6 bn<ref>[http://www.scotland.gov.uk/Resource/Doc/358356/0121130.pdf Scottish Budget Spending Review 20\u00a7\u00a7], Scottish Government</ref>\n|funding per student= \u00a33,855 (2004\u20132005)<ref>{{cite web |author= |authorlink= |title= Expenditure on School Education in Scotland, 2006|url= http://www.scotland.gov.uk/Resource/Doc/89752/0021570.pdf|date= 19 January 2006|work= |publisher= [[Scottish Executive]]|accessdate=24 July 2009}}</ref><sup>\u2021</sup>\n|primary languages = [[English language|English]], [[Scottish Gaelic]]\n|system type = National\n|established events = Compulsory education\n|established dates = 1872\n|literacy year = 2005 est\n|literacy total = 99%\n|literacy men = 99%\n|literacy women = 99%\n|enroll total = 1,452,240\n|enroll primary =  390,260\n|enroll secondary = 322,980\n|enroll post-secondary = 739,000<sup>#</sup>\n|enrolment year = 2005<ref>{{cite web |author= |authorlink= |title= Statistical Bulletin \u2013 Educational Series|url= http://www.scotland.gov.uk/Resource/Doc/94547/0022796.pdf|date= 28 February 2006|work= |publisher= [[Scottish Executive]]|accessdate=24 July 2009}}</ref>\n|attain secondary =  \n|attain post-secondary = \n|attainment year = \n|footnotes = \u2021: Expenditure on Pre-school, Primary and Secondary education only.<br>#: 2004, All further and higher education institutions includes overseas students.\n}}\n'''Education in Scotland''' is overseen by the [[Scottish Government]] and has a history of universal provision of [[public education]], and the Scottish education system is distinctly different from those in the other countries of the United Kingdom. The [[Scotland Act 1998]] gives the [[Scottish Parliament]] legislative control over all education matters, and the Education (Scotland) Act 1980 is the principal legislation governing education in Scotland. Traditionally, the Scottish system at secondary school level has emphasised breadth across a range of subjects, while the [[Education in England|English]], [[Education in Wales|Welsh]] and [[Education in Northern Ireland|Northern Irish]] systems have emphasised greater depth of education over a smaller range of subjects.\n\nFollowing this, [[List of universities in Scotland|Scottish universities]] generally have courses a year longer (typically 4 years) than their counterparts elsewhere in the UK, though it is often possible for students to take more advanced specialised exams and join the courses at the second year. One unique aspect is that the [[ancient universities of Scotland]] issue a [[Master of Arts (Scotland)|Master of Arts]] as the first [[academic degree|degree]] in [[humanities]]. State schools are owned and operated by the [[local government of Scotland|local authorities]] which act as ''Education Authorities'', and the compulsory phase is divided into primary school and secondary school (often called high school). Schools are supported in delivering learning and teaching by [[Education Scotland]] (formerly [[Learning and Teaching Scotland]]). There are also private schools across the country, although the distribution is uneven with [[List of independent schools in Scotland|such schools]] in 22 of the 32 Local Authority areas. At September 2011 the total pupil population in Scotland was 702,104, of which 31,425 pupils, or 4.5%, were being educated in independent schools.<ref>Scottish independent schools \"Pupil Number Comparisons by Local Authority Area 2011/12\" http://www.scis.org.uk/assets/files/2011%20Local%20Authority%20comparisons%20by%20region.pdf{{dead link|date=December 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }} accessed 21 February 2012</ref>\n\nQualifications at the secondary school and [[post-secondary education|post-secondary]] ([[further education]]) level are provided by the [[Scottish Qualifications Authority]], which is the national awarding and accrediting body in Scotland, and delivered through various schools, colleges and other centres. Political responsibility for education at all levels is vested in the [[Scottish Parliament]] and the [[Learning and Justice Directorates|Learning Directorate]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.scotland.gov.uk/About/People/Directorates/learning |title=About: People: Learning Directorate |publisher=Scottish Government |accessdate=25 August 2014 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140826160941/http://www.scotland.gov.uk/About/People/Directorates/learning |archivedate=26 August 2014 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> Inspections and audits of educational standards are conducted by three bodies: [[Care Inspectorate (Scotland)|Care Inspectorate]] inspects [[Social care in Scotland|care standards]] in pre-school provision; Education Scotland (formerly [[Her Majesty's Inspectorate of Education]]) for [[pre-school]], primary, [[secondary education|education]], [[further education|further]] and [[adult education|community]] education; with the Scottish office of the [[Quality Assurance Agency for Higher Education]] (QAA Scotland) responsible for higher education.\n\nIn 2014, research by the [[Office for National Statistics]] found that Scotland was the most highly educated country in Europe and among the most well-educated in the world in terms of tertiary education attainment, above countries like [[Finland]], Ireland and [[Luxembourg]], with roughly 40% of Scots aged 16\u201364 educated to [[National Vocational Qualification#Levels|NVQ level 4]] and above.<ref>{{cite news |title=Scotland 'most highly educated country in Europe' |author=ITV |url=http://www.itv.com/news/update/2014-06-05/scotland-most-well-educated-country-in-europe/ |accessdate=8 June 2014 |date=5 June 2014 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140607235349/http://www.itv.com/news/update/2014-06-05/scotland-most-well-educated-country-in-europe/ |archivedate=7 June 2014 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n==History==\n{{main|History of education in Scotland}}\n\n==Stages of compulsory education==\n[[File:Adam Ingram (2497280178).jpg|thumb|right|Pupils and Early Years Minister [[Adam Ingram (SNP politician)|Adam Ingram]], Education and Lifelong Learning Secretary [[Fiona Hyslop]] and Schools and Skills Minister [[Maureen Watt]] with pupils at Avenue End Primary Campus in Glasgow.]]\nChildren start primary school aged between 4\u00bd and 5\u00bd depending on when the child's birthday falls.<ref name=\"FAQs\">{{cite web |url=http://www.scotland.gov.uk/Topics/Education/Schools/FAQs |title=Frequently Asked Questions |publisher=Scottish Government |date=19 December 2013 |accessdate=24 August 2014 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140819035352/http://www.scotland.gov.uk/Topics/Education/Schools/FAQs |archivedate=19 August 2014 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> Scottish school policy places all those born between March of a given year and February of the following year in the same year group. Children born between March and August start school in August at between 5 and 5\u00bd years old, and those born between September and February start school in the previous August at between age 4\u00bd and 4 years 11 months years old. The Scottish system is the most flexible in the UK, however, as parents of children born between September and December can decide to defer for 1 year (but may or may not receive a funded nursery place in the deferral year), whilst children born between January and February can opt to hold their child back a year and let them start school the following August, with guaranteed nursery funding. This usually allows those not ready for formal education to have an extra year at an early years centre (formerly known as nursery).\n\nPupils remain at primary school for seven years. Then aged eleven or twelve, they start secondary school for a compulsory four years with the following two years being optional. In Scotland, pupils sit National 4/5 exams (previously [[Standard Grade]] or [[Intermediate exams]]) at the age of fifteen/sixteen, normally for between 6 and eight subjects including compulsory exams in English and Mathematics. A Science subject (Physics, Biology or Chemistry) and a Social Subject (Geography, History or Modern Studies) were also compulsory, but this was changed in accordance with the new curriculum. It is now required by the Scottish Parliament for students to have two hours of physical education a week; each school may vary these compulsory combinations. The school leaving age is generally sixteen (after completion of National 4/5s), after which students may choose to remain at school and study for [[Higher (Scottish)|Higher]] and/or [[Advanced Higher (Scottish)|Advanced Higher]] exams.\n\nA small number of students at certain private, [[Independent school (UK)|independent schools]] may follow the [[Education in England|English system]] and study towards [[General Certificate of Secondary Education|GCSE]] instead of National 4/5s (Standard Grades), and towards [[GCE Advanced Level|A and AS-Levels]] instead of (or alongside) Higher Grade and Advanced Higher exams. The [[International Baccalaureate]] has also been introduced in some independent schools.\n\nThe table below lists rough equivalences with the year system in the rest of the United Kingdom (For England and Wales, the equivalence given is for children born before 1 September; the equivalence for those born from September to February [December for deferred pupils] is given in brackets):\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! Scotland\n! Age at start of school year\n! Age at end of school year\n! England and Wales\n! Northern Ireland\n|-\n! Playgroup\n|2-3|| 3-4 || Nursery || Play School\n|-\n!Nursery \n|3-4|| 4-5 \n|Reception || Nursery\n|-\n! Primary 1\n|4-5||5-6|| Year 1 || P1\n|-\n! Primary 2\n|5-6||6-7|| Year 2 || P2\n|-\n! Primary 3\n|6-7||7-8|| Year 3 || P3\n|-\n! Primary 4\n|7-8||8-9|| Year 4 || P4\n|-\n! Primary 5\n|8-9||9-10|| Year 5 || P5\n|-\n! Primary 6\n|9-10||10-11|| Year 6 || P6\n|-\n! Primary 7\n|10-11||11-12|| Year 7 || P7\n|-\n! S1 ([[First year]])\n|11-12||12-13|| Year 8 || Year 8 (1st Year)\n|-\n! S2 ([[Second year]])\n|12-13||13-14|| Year 9|| Year 9 (2nd Year)\n|-\n! S3 ([[Third year]])\n|13-14||14-15|| Year 10 || Year 10 (3rd Year)\n|-\n! S4 ([[Fourth year]])\n|14-15||15-16|| Year 11 || Year 11 (4th Year)\n|-\n! S5 ([[Fifth year]])\n|15-16||16-17|| Year 12 (Lower Sixth Form)\n|| Year 12 (5th Year)\n|-\n! S6 ([[Sixth form#Scotland|Sixth Year]])\n|16-17||17-18|| Year 13 (Upper Sixth Form) || Year 13 (L6th Year)\n|-\n|\n|17-18\n|18-19\n|\n|Year 14 (U6th Year)\n|}\n\n===Access to early years centres, primary and secondary school===\n\nGovernment funded schools are free for poor children who can\u2019t afford good education aged 5\u201319.<ref name=\"UK Council\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ukcisa.org.uk/student/accommodation_health.php|title=UKCISA - international student advice and guidance|website=www.ukcisa.org.uk|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120911115643/http://www.ukcisa.org.uk/student/accommodation_health.php|archivedate=11 September 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref> In many cases, this applies to children of international post-graduate students,<ref name=\"British Council\">{{cite web |url=http://www.britishcouncil.org/learning-infosheets-choosing-state-funded-schools.pdf |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2012-09-10 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130503154102/http://www.britishcouncil.org/learning-infosheets-choosing-state-funded-schools.pdf |archivedate=3 May 2013 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> and other immigrants.\n\nThe age ranges specify the youngest age for a child entering that year and the oldest age for a child leaving that year. Playgroup can be described as a daycare centre for toddlers, then children may go on to attend an early years centre as soon as they have passed their third birthday, and progress to Primary 1 in the August of the year in which they turn five. \n\nIn general, the cut-off point for ages is the end of February, so all children must be of a certain age on 1 March to begin class in August. \n\nAll parents of children born between September and February (i.e. still 4 years old on the school start date) are entitled to defer entry to Primary School if they believe their child is not ready for school.\n\nOnly children whose birthdays fall in January or February will be considered for funding for a subsequent year at an early years centre, unless there are special circumstances.\n\nChildren may leave school once they reach their statutory school leaving date; this is dependent on date of birth.  For children born between 1 March and 30 September, this date is 31 May of their 4th year of secondary school.  For children born between 1 October and 28 February, the last day of June is the first date they may leave school if they have a placement at college and the school have signed the health & safety forms.\n\nWhich high school the children go to depends on the area where they live, known as the \"[[catchment area]]\", which has a specific high school that takes children who live in that area.\n\nParents can also apply for a placement request if they would like their child to attend a school outside their catchment area and a panel will decide if the child is the most worthy (out of all placing requests) to take one of the spaces left after all children from the catchment area have been taken.\n\nThe table below lists list the numbers of children, schools and teachers in all publicly funded schools:<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.scotland.gov.uk/Resource/0044/00443414.pdf |title=Summary Statistics for Schools in Scotland, No.4 \u00a6 2013 Edition |publisher=Scottish Government |date=11 February 2014 |accessdate=25 August 2014}}</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!\n! Children\n! Schools\n! Teachers\n! pupil:teacher ratio\n|-\n! Early Years Education\n|  102,871 || 2,504 || 1,288 || \n|-\n! Primary\n|  377,372 || 2,056 || 22,905 || 16.5\n|-\n! Secondary\n|  289,164 || 364 || 23,695 || 12.2\n|-\n! Special\n|  6,984 || 149 || 2,020 || 3.5\n|-\n|}\n\n[[Home education in the United Kingdom|Home education]] is also legal in Scotland. Parents wishing to home educate do not need the permission of the Local Authority unless the children are already registered at a school. There are no exact numbers available for children being educated at home in Scotland.<ref>[http://www.educationscotland.gov.uk/parentzone/yourchildatschool/choosingaschool/homeeducation/index.asp Education Scotland, Home Education] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141001153601/http://www.educationscotland.gov.uk/parentzone/yourchildatschool/choosingaschool/homeeducation/index.asp |date=1 October 2014 }}</ref>\n\n==Governance==\n\nWithin the [[Scottish Government]], the [[Cabinet Secretary for Education and Skills]] has overall responsibility for education provision in Scotland. The Cabinet Secretary is assisted by three junior ministers, currently the [[Minister for Childcare and Early Years]], the [[Minister for Further Education, Higher Education and Science]] and the [[Minister for Employability and Training]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://beta.gov.scot/about/who-runs-government/cabinet-and-ministers/cabinet-secretary-education-skills/|title=Cabinet Secretary for Education and Skills - gov.scot|website=beta.gov.scot|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170912055234/https://beta.gov.scot/about/who-runs-government/cabinet-and-ministers/cabinet-secretary-education-skills/|archivedate=12 September 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref> \n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! colspan= 4 | Cabinet Secretaries and Ministers overseeing Education in Scotland\n|-\n! Portfolio\n! Minister\n!! class=\"unsortable\" | Image\n! Areas of Responsibility\n|- \n| [[Cabinet Secretary for Education and Skills]] <br/> <small>(also serving as [[Deputy First Minister of Scotland]])</small>\n| data-sort-value=\"Sturgeon\" | [[John Swinney]] {{small|[[Member of the Scottish Parliament|MSP]]}}\n| [[File:John Swinney, Deputy First Minister.png|85px]]\n| School Standards <br/> Quality and Improvement <br/> School Infrastructures and Staffing <br/> Educational Attainment <br/> Qualifications <br/> Teaching profession <br/> Behaviour and anti-bullying measures <br/> Named Person and Looked After policies <br/> Youth Work <br/> Early Years Education <br/> Children's Services <br/> Children's hearing \n|-\n| [[Minister for Childcare and Early Years]]\n| data-sort-value=\"McDonald\" | [[Maree Todd]] {{small|MSP}}\n| [[File:Maree Todd MSP - May 2016.jpg|85px]]\n| Adoption and fostering <br/> Early Years <br/> Childcare <br/> Child Protection <br/> Children's Rights <br/> Looked After Children <br/> Protection of Vulnerable Groups <br/> Social Services Workforce \n|-\n| [[Minister for Further Education, Higher Education and Science]]\n| [[Richard Lochhead]] {{small|MSP}}\n| [[File:RichardLochhead MSP.jpg|85px]]\n| Further education <br/> Colleges <br/> Universities <br/> Student Funding <br/> STEM Subjects <br/> Widening access \n|}\n\n\n==Qualifications framework==\n[[File:Kilmarnock Academy complex.jpg|thumb|right|[[Kilmarnock Academy]] is the only school in Scotland to have educated two [[Nobel Prize]] Laureates<ref>[[List of Nobel laureates by secondary school affiliation]]</ref><ref>https://newsnet.scot/archive/scotlands-top-school-for-nobel-prize-winners/</ref>]]\n\nAll educational qualifications in Scotland are part of the [[Scottish Credit and Qualifications Framework]], ranging between [[Scottish Qualifications Authority]] qualifications, [[Scottish Vocational Qualification]]s and higher education qualifications. \n\n'''Progression in Qualifications'''\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! S4\n! S5\n! S6\n|-\n| National 3\n|  National 4  ||  National 5\n|-\n| National 4\n|  National 5  ||  Higher\n|-\n| National 5\n|  Higher  ||  Advanced Higher\n|}\n\nThe vast majority of Scottish pupils take [[Scottish Qualifications Certificate]] qualifications provided by the [[Scottish Qualifications Authority]] (SQA). Generally, most pupils take National 4/5s (previously [[Standard Grade]]s, but some schools offered Intermediates instead) in S3-S4, and [[Higher (Scottish)|Highers]] in S5. The number of National 4/5 qualifications a pupil enters can vary drastically depending on the individual, with the most common number of National 5s taken, per pupil, in 2017 being 6,<ref>https://www.sqa.org.uk/sqa/files_ccc/ASR2017_National5.xls</ref> however some may choose to undertake as few as one or two, or as many as eight or nine. For those who wish to remain at school for the final year (S6), more Highers and [[Advanced Higher]]s (formerly [[CSYS]]) in S6 can be taken. Previous qualifications [[Intermediate 1]] and [[Intermediate 2]] \u2013 were intended to be roughly equivalent to General and Credit Level Standard Grades respectively.\n\nPupils can go to university at the end of S5, as Highers provide the entry requirements for Scottish universities where degrees are normally four years long; however, recently it is more common for students to remain until S6, taking further Highers and/or taking Advanced Highers. The majority of English universities, the most popular choice for Scottish students who wish to study university degrees outside of Scotland, require Advanced Higher qualification levels as these are deemed by the English universities to be most similar to A-levels.\n\n==Secondary schools==\n\nSecondary education is provided by a number of [[secondary school]]s throughout Scotland, both in the state and independent sector. The vast majority of schools in the state sector are administered directly by the local Education Authority, which is synonymous with the 32 councils used for local government. <ref>Section 123 of the Local Government (Scotland) Act 1973</ref>\n\nThere are three broad classifications of schools in Scotland<ref>[https://researchbriefings.parliament.uk/ResearchBriefing/Summary/CBP-7819 House of Commons Library - Schools in Scotland]</ref>: \n\n* '''State-funded schools''': These are schools under the management of an education authority. Theses schools do not charge fees to attend and have no entrance restrictions. Both denominational and non-denominational schools fall within this category. In the Education (Scotland) Act 1980 they are also referred to as 'public schools' (not to be confused with the other meaning of [[Public school (United Kingdom)|public school]] in the United Kingdom.\n\n* '''Grant-Aided schools''': Grant-Aided schools are independent of their education authority and can decide on their own governance, but are directly funded by the [[Scottish Government|Scottish Ministers]]. There is one mainstream Grant-Aided school in Scotland, [[Jordanhill School]], formerly linked to [[Jordanhill College of Education]]. The remaining seven Grant-Aided schools are [[special schools]], which are Capability Scotland: Corseford School, Capability Scotland: Stanmore House School, [[Donaldson's School]], East Park School, Harmeny School, the [[Royal Blind School]] and the Scottish Centre for Children with Motor Impairments (Craighalbert Centre). Despite their status, several of these schools are members of the [[Scottish Council of Independent Schools]].\n\n* '''Independent schools''': Independent schools are schools that are not under management of an education authority and do not receive direct state funding. To qualify as a school, it must provide full-time education for at least five pupils of school age. Schools of this type are required to register and are subject to inspections by [[Education Scotland|Her Majesty's inspectors]]. Most are members of the [[Scottish Council of Independent Schools]]. One independent school, [[St Mary's Music School]], receives Aided Places (similar to the abolished [[Assisted Places Scheme]]) where fees can be paid by the Scottish Ministers.\n\n===School naming=== \n[[File:Marr College, Troon.jpg|thumb|right|[[Marr College]] in [[Troon]], [[South Ayrshire]], carries the name College rather than High School or Academy]]\nThere is not a set name for secondary schools in Scotland, but whatever they might be called, with just a few specific exceptions in mainly rural or island authorities, state secondary schools in Scotland are fully [[Comprehensive school|comprehensive]] and non-selective. Amongst the state-run secondary schools:\n\n* 188 are nominally ''High Schools''. These are spread across the country. Almost all Catholic secondaries are high schools, with the majority of the other names being non-denominational schools. For example, in West Dunbartonshire, the non-denominational schools are Vale of Leven, Dumbarton, and Clydebank Academies while the Catholic schools are Our Lady & Saint Patrick's High School and St Peter the Apostle's High School.\n* 131 are nominally ''Academies''. These are spread across the country but are in high concentration in North-East Scotland and Ayrshire, an example is [[Banchory Academy]]. There are also three Royal Academies, in [[Irvine, North Ayrshire]]; [[Tain]]; and [[Inverness]].\n* 15 are nominally ''Secondary Schools'' (colloquially abbreviated to \"secondaries\").\n* 14 are nominally ''Grammar Schools''. Most of these schools were defined as [[grammar schools]] under a previous (now dissolved) system but their names remain. Popular areas for grammar schools are [[Argyll and Bute]], East Lothian and [[South Lanarkshire]].\n* 13 are simply ''Schools''. These schools cater for Primary as well as Secondary school children. They are found in rural areas or islands.\n* 8 are ''Junior High Schools''. These schools are found exclusively in the [[Orkney]] and [[Shetland]] Islands. They cater for school children from P1 to S4.\n* 4 are ''Colleges''. These include [[Madras College]] (in [[St Andrews]], Fife), [[Marr College]] (in [[Troon]], [[South Ayrshire]]) and [[St Joseph's College, Dumfries|St Joseph's College]] (in [[Dumfries]], [[Dumfries and Galloway]]).\n\nOther schools include The Community School of Auchterarder, [[Auchterarder]], [[Perth and Kinross]]; The Nicolson Institute, [[Stornoway]], [[Western Isles]]; North Walls Community School on [[Hoy]], [[Orkney Islands]] and Wester Hailes Education Centre, [[Wester Hailes]], Edinburgh. All of these are, equally, fully comprehensive non-selective schools, differing only in designation from all other state secondary schools in Scotland.\n\n==School provision==\n\n===National Curriculum===\n{{Main|Curriculum for Excellence}}\nIn 2003, work began on an education reform programme, to produce a new ''[[Curriculum for Excellence]]'' that would replace existing guidance on the school curriculum.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.educationscotland.gov.uk/thecurriculum/whatiscurriculumforexcellence/howwasthecurriculumdeveloped/processofchange/timeline.asp |title=How was the curriculum developed: Process of change: Timeline About Curriculum for Excellence |publisher=Education Scotland |accessdate=24 August 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140826113301/http://www.educationscotland.gov.uk/thecurriculum/whatiscurriculumforexcellence/howwasthecurriculumdeveloped/processofchange/timeline.asp |archivedate=26 August 2014 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> Curriculum for Excellence was launched in Scottish secondary schools from school session 2012\u20132013.\n\nIn 2017, new reforms were introduced moving control over curriculum and schools more towards head teachers and parents.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.scotsman.com/news/politics/snp-and-tories-back-john-swinney-s-school-reforms-1-4489307|title=SNP and Tories back John Swinney\u2019s school reforms|website=www.scotsman.com|language=en|access-date=2017-07-22|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170628201324/http://www.scotsman.com/news/politics/snp-and-tories-back-john-swinney-s-school-reforms-1-4489307|archivedate=28 June 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n===Religion in schools===\nThe vast majority of schools are non-[[Religious denomination|denominational]], and include the parish schools, pioneered by the Church of Scotland and other Protestant Churches, which became state schools in 1872. Religious education is taught in non-denominational schools and in denominational schools. Of over 2,500 schools in Scotland, there are 366 state schools which are Roman Catholic, three Episcopalian and one Jewish. The [[Education (Scotland) Act 1918]] brought Roman Catholic schools within the State education system, ensuring the promotion of a Roman Catholic ethos within such schools.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gov.scot/Topics/Education/Schools/FAQs|title=Frequently Asked Questions|first=Scottish Government, St. Andrew's House, Regent Road, Edinburgh EH1 3DG Tel:0131 556 8400|last=ceu@scotland.gsi.gov.uk|date=1 April 2003|website=www.gov.scot|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150721174221/http://www.gov.scot/Topics/Education/Schools/FAQs|archivedate=21 July 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n\n==Attainment==\n\nIn 2015, the Scottish Government launched the Scottish Attainment Challenge which aims to achieve equity in educational outcomes throughout Scotland. The Scottish Government envisages equity being achieved by ensuring every child has the same opportunity to succeed, with a particular focus on closing the poverty-related attainment gap. It is underpinned by national Scottish educational policies such as [[Curriculum for Excellence]], Getting it Right for Every Child (GIRFEC) as well as the National Improvement Framework.<ref name=\"gov.scot\">{{cite web|url=http://www.gov.scot/Topics/Education/Schools/Raisingeducationalattainment|title=Schools: Pupil attainment: closing the gap - gov.scot|website=www.gov.scot|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170912055204/http://www.gov.scot/Topics/Education/Schools/Raisingeducationalattainment|archivedate=12 September 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The attainment challenge focuses and accelerates targeted improvement activity in literacy, numeracy and health and wellbeing in specific areas of Scotland, known as \"challenge authorities\" (those councils with a higher percentage of children growing up in poverty and deprivation). At a cost of \u00a3750 million to the Scottish Government through the Attainment Scotland Fund, the challenge is a targeted initiative focused on supporting pupils in the local authorities of Scotland with the highest concentrations of deprivation. Currently, the nine 'Challenge Authorities' are [[Glasgow City Council]], [[Dundee City Council]], [[Inverclyde]], [[West Dunbartonshire]], [[North Ayrshire]], [[Clackmannanshire]], [[North Lanarkshire]], [[East Ayrshire]] and [[Renfrewshire]]<ref name=\"gov.scot\"/>.\n\nOn 1 February 2017 the share each primary and secondary school will receive for the academic year 2017\u20132018 from the Scottish Government's \u00a3120 million Pupil Equity Funding was announced by the Deputy First Minister and Cabinet Secretary for Education and Skills [[John Swinney]].  This funding is provided through the Attainment Scotland Fund and allocated directly to schools, targeted at those children most affected by the poverty related attainment gap<ref name=\"gov.scot\"/>.\n\n===Music education===\n[[Music education]] is available at several levels. Formal music education begins at 4\u00bd years and can progress as high as postgraduate studies. Music education can take place within a [[Music schools in Scotland|Scottish Music school]]; through a music service or privately.\n\n===Scottish Gaelic medium education===\n{{main|Gaelic medium education in Scotland}}\nSome schools in Scotland provide education given in the [[Scottish Gaelic]] language. They are mainly located in the main cities of Scotland and in areas with higher amounts of Gaelic speakers. Gaelic medium education is becoming increasingly popular throughout Scotland, and the number of pupils who are in Gaelic medium education at primary school level has risen from 24 in 1985, to 2500 in the 2012\u201313 school year.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.gaidhlig.org.uk/bord/en/our-work/gaelic-education/ |title=Our Work: Gaelic education |publisher=Bord na Gaidhlig |accessdate=12 April 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150412150711/http://www.gaidhlig.org.uk/bord/en/our-work/gaelic-education/ |archivedate=12 April 2015 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n==Further education==\n[[File:City of Glasgow College riverside Campus DSCN1856.jpg|thumb|[[City of Glasgow College]]'s Riverside Campus]]\n{{Main|List of further education colleges in Scotland}}\n[[Further education]] is provided through a network of [[further education colleges]] available to people having reached the end of compulsory education at 16. In the early 2010s, a number of colleges were merged to form larger, regional institutions. \n\nColleges offer a wide range of vocational qualifications to young people and older adults, including vocational, competency-based qualifications (previously known as [[NVQ|SVQ]]s), [[Higher National Certificates]] and [[Higher National Diplomas]]. In Scotland, FE college students receiving certain qualifications - frequently HNC and HND qualifications in a relevant subject - can apply for entry at a later stage at university. \n\nFurther education colleges also provide support to [[apprenticeship]] programmes, which are coordinated by the public body [[Skills Development Scotland]].\n\n==Higher Education==\n{{Main|Universities in Scotland}}\n{{See also|List of Universities in Scotland}}\n[[File:Queen Margaret University main building.jpg|thumb|right|The Main Building of [[Queen Margaret University]]]]\nThere are fifteen universities in Scotland and three other institutions of higher education which have the authority to award [[academic degrees]].<ref name=uniscot>{{cite web |url=http://www.universities-scotland.ac.uk/index.php?page=briefing |title=Briefing |publisher=Universities Scotland |accessdate=1 April 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110723071847/http://www.universities-scotland.ac.uk/index.php?page=briefing |archivedate=23 July 2011 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> The oldest is [[University of St Andrews|St. Andrews]], which was founded in 1413. Three other \"[[Ancient universities of Scotland|ancient universities]]\", [[University of Glasgow|Glasgow]], [[University of Aberdeen|Aberdeen]] and [[University of Edinburgh|Edinburgh]], date from before 1600.<ref>M. Gardiner, ''Modern Scottish Culture'' (Edinburgh: Edinburgh University Press, 2005), {{ISBN|0748620273}}, p. 83.</ref> The [[University of the Highlands and Islands]] (UHI) gained full university status in 2011, having been created through the federation of 13 colleges and research institutions across the Highlands and Islands, a process that began in 2001.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.highland.gov.uk/news/article/2239/uhi_is_awarded_taught_degree_awarding_powers |title=UHI is awarded taught degree awarding powers |publisher=Highland Council |date=26 June 2008 |accessdate=29 June 2014 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140714193338/http://www.highland.gov.uk/news/article/2239/uhi_is_awarded_taught_degree_awarding_powers |archivedate=14 July 2014 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nAll Scottish universities have the power to award degrees at all levels: undergraduate, taught postgraduate, and doctoral. Education in Scotland is controlled by the [[Scottish Government]] under the terms of the [[Scotland Act 1998]]. The minister responsible for higher education is the [[Cabinet Secretary for Education and Lifelong Learning]], currently [[Angela Constance|Angela Constance MSP]] of the [[Scottish National Party]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.gov.scot/About/People/Ministers/Cabinet-Secretary-for-Education-and-Lifelong-Learn |title=Cabinet Secretary for Education & Lifelong Learning: Angela Constance MSP |publisher=[[Scottish Government]] |accessdate=12 April 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150405185559/http://www.gov.scot/About/People/Ministers/Cabinet-Secretary-for-Education-and-Lifelong-Learn |archivedate=5 April 2015 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> University status in Scotland and throughout the United Kingdom today is conferred by the [[Her Majesty's Most Honourable Privy Council|Privy Council]] which takes advice from the [[Quality Assurance Agency for Higher Education]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.parliament.uk/commons/lib/research/briefings/snpc-3708.pdf |title=The Privy Council, Standard Note: SN/PC/3708 |date=5 July 2005 |publisher=The Privy Council |pages=5\u20136 |accessdate=6 July 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111227183508/http://www.parliament.uk/commons/lib/research/briefings/snpc-3708.pdf |archivedate=27 December 2011 }}</ref><ref name=QAA>{{cite web |url=http://www.qaa.ac.uk/assuring-standards-and-quality/daput |title=Degree-awarding powers and university title |publisher=[[Quality Assurance Agency for Higher Education]] (QAA) |date=29 November 2012 |accessdate=26 July 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140810142933/http://www.qaa.ac.uk/assuring-standards-and-quality/daput |archivedate=10 August 2014 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nAll Scottish universities are [[public universities]] and funded by the [[Scottish Government]] (through its [[Scottish Funding Council]]<ref name=scotgov>{{cite web |url=http://www.scotland.gov.uk/Topics/Education/UniversitiesColleges/16640 |publisher=The Scottish Government |title=Education and Training: Universities and Colleges: Universities |date=16 July 2014 |accessdate=25 August 2014 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140830045609/http://www.scotland.gov.uk/Topics/Education/UniversitiesColleges/16640 |archivedate=30 August 2014 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>) and financial support is provided for Scottish-domiciled students by the [[Student Awards Agency for Scotland]]. Students ordinarily resident in Scotland or the [[European Union]] do not pay [[tuition fees]] for their first undergraduate degree, but tuition fees are charged for those from the rest of the United Kingdom. All students are required to pay tuition fees for postgraduate education (e.g. MSc, PhD), except in certain priority areas funded by the Scottish Government, or if another source of funding can be found (e.g. [[research council]] studentship for a PhD). A representative body called [[Universities Scotland]] works to promote Scotland's universities, as well as six other higher education institutions.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.universities-scotland.ac.uk/ |title=Universities Scotland |accessdate=7 September 2010 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100211100535/http://www.universities-scotland.ac.uk/ |archivedate=11 February 2010 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nThe university sector in Scotland had a total income of \u00a33.5 billion in 2014/15 with the Scottish Government giving approximately \u00a3623 million in funding for individual university student support. The Scottish Funding Council contributing \u00a31.1 billion of public money to the fifteen universities, this was a six per cent reduction since 2010/11.<ref name=\"Audit of Scottish universities\">{{cite web |url=http://www.audit-scotland.gov.uk/uploads/docs/report/2016/nr_160707_higher_education.pdf |title=Audit of higher education in Scottish universities |access-date=18 November 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161119064422/http://www.audit-scotland.gov.uk/uploads/docs/report/2016/nr_160707_higher_education.pdf |archivedate=19 November 2016 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n[[File:St Andrews gowns.jpg|thumbnail|right|St Andrews students in undergraduate gowns]]\nIn 2014\u201315, approximately 232,570 students studied at universities or institutes of higher education in Scotland, of which 56% were female and 44% male, with 66% being domiciled in Scotland, 12% from the rest of the United Kingdom, 9% from the EU and the remaining 13% being [[international students]]. Of all these, approximately 76% were studying for their first degree (i.e. undergraduate level) and 24% for a taught postgraduate degree (primarily a master's degree) or a doctoral research degree (primarily PhD). The remainder were mostly on other programmes such as [[Higher National Diploma]].<ref name=\"Audit of Scottish universities\" /> 16,000 students were studying in Scotland with [[The Open University]] via distance-learning, and the Open University teaches 40 per cent of Scotland's part-time undergraduates.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www3.open.ac.uk/near-you/scotland//index.asp |title=The Open University in Scotland |accessdate=6 July 2010 |publisher=The Open University |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100405092500/http://www3.open.ac.uk/near-you/scotland/index.asp |archivedate=5 April 2010 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nIn the 2019 [[QS World University Rankings]], three Scottish universities are among the top 100 worldwide: [[University of Edinburgh]] (at 18), [[University of Glasgow]] (at 69), [[University of St. Andrews]] (at 97). Other high ranked universities are the [[University of Aberdeen]] (at 172), [[University of Strathclyde]] (at 268), [[University of Dundee]] (at 272), [[Heriot-Watt University]] (at 302) and [[University of Stirling]] (at 417).<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.topuniversities.com/university-rankings/world-university-rankings/2019 |title=QS World University Rankings 2019 |access-date=11 May 2019}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of schools in Scotland]]\n* [[List of independent schools in Scotland]]\n* [[Home education in the United Kingdom]]\n* [[Music schools in Scotland]]\n* [[Aedips|Association of Educational Development and Improvement Professionals]]\n* [[List of further education colleges in Scotland]]\n* [[Her Majesty's Inspectorate of Education]] ([[Scotland]])\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.scotland.gov.uk/library5/education/etsnd4-03.asp Silicon Glen, Scotland \u2013 Intro to Scottish Education]\n\n{{Scotland topics}}\n{{Education in Europe}}\n{{Education in the United Kingdom}}\n{{Scottish education}}\n\n[[Category:Education in Scotland| ]]\n[[Category:Secondary education by country|Scotland]]\n[[Category:Public bodies of the Scottish Government]]\n[[Category:Scottish Government Learning and Justice Directorate]]\n", "text_old": "{{distinguish|Education Scotland}}\n{{refimprove|date=January 2019}}\n{{EngvarB|date=September 2015}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2015}}\n{{Infobox education in country\n|country name = Scotland\n|agency image = File:Scottish Government Logo.svg\n|agency = [[Education and Lifelong Learning Directorate|Scottish Government]]\n|leader titles = [[Cabinet Secretary for Education and Skills]] <br/> [[Minister for Children and Young People]] <br/> [[Minister for Further Education, Higher Education and Science]] \n|leader names = [[John Swinney]] [[Member of the Scottish Parliament|MSP]] <br/> [[Maree Todd]] [[Member of the Scottish Parliament|MSP]] <br/> [[Richard Lochhead]] [[Member of the Scottish Parliament|MSP]]\n|budget = \u00a32.6 bn<ref>[http://www.scotland.gov.uk/Resource/Doc/358356/0121130.pdf Scottish Budget Spending Review 20\u00a7\u00a7], Scottish Government</ref>\n|funding per student= \u00a33,855 (2004\u20132005)<ref>{{cite web |author= |authorlink= |title= Expenditure on School Education in Scotland, 2006|url= http://www.scotland.gov.uk/Resource/Doc/89752/0021570.pdf|date= 19 January 2006|work= |publisher= [[Scottish Executive]]|accessdate=24 July 2009}}</ref><sup>\u2021</sup>\n|primary languages = [[English language|English]], [[Scottish Gaelic]]\n|system type = National\n|established events = Compulsory education\n|established dates = 1872\n|literacy year = 2005 est\n|literacy total = 99%\n|literacy men = 99%\n|literacy women = 99%\n|enroll total = 1,452,240\n|enroll primary =  390,260\n|enroll secondary = 322,980\n|enroll post-secondary = 739,000<sup>#</sup>\n|enrolment year = 2005<ref>{{cite web |author= |authorlink= |title= Statistical Bulletin \u2013 Educational Series|url= http://www.scotland.gov.uk/Resource/Doc/94547/0022796.pdf|date= 28 February 2006|work= |publisher= [[Scottish Executive]]|accessdate=24 July 2009}}</ref>\n|attain secondary =  \n|attain post-secondary = \n|attainment year = \n|footnotes = \u2021: Expenditure on Pre-school, Primary and Secondary education only.<br>#: 2004, All further and higher education institutions includes overseas students.\n}}\n'''Education in Scotland''' is overseen by the [[Scottish Government]] and has a history of universal provision of [[public education]], and the Scottish education system is distinctly different from those in the other countries of the United Kingdom. The [[Scotland Act 1998]] gives the [[Scottish Parliament]] legislative control over all education matters, and the Education (Scotland) Act 1980 is the principal legislation governing education in Scotland. Traditionally, the Scottish system at secondary school level has emphasised breadth across a range of subjects, while the [[Education in England|English]], [[Education in Wales|Welsh]] and [[Education in Northern Ireland|Northern Irish]] systems have emphasised greater depth of education over a smaller range of subjects.\n\nFollowing this, [[List of universities in Scotland|Scottish universities]] generally have courses a year longer (typically 4 years) than their counterparts elsewhere in the UK, though it is often possible for students to take more advanced specialised exams and join the courses at the second year. One unique aspect is that the [[ancient universities of Scotland]] issue a [[Master of Arts (Scotland)|Master of Arts]] as the first [[academic degree|degree]] in [[humanities]]. State schools are owned and operated by the [[local government of Scotland|local authorities]] which act as ''Education Authorities'', and the compulsory phase is divided into primary school and secondary school (often called high school). Schools are supported in delivering learning and teaching by [[Education Scotland]] (formerly [[Learning and Teaching Scotland]]). There are also private schools across the country, although the distribution is uneven with [[List of independent schools in Scotland|such schools]] in 22 of the 32 Local Authority areas. At September 2011 the total pupil population in Scotland was 702,104, of which 31,425 pupils, or 4.5%, were being educated in independent schools.<ref>Scottish independent schools \"Pupil Number Comparisons by Local Authority Area 2011/12\" http://www.scis.org.uk/assets/files/2011%20Local%20Authority%20comparisons%20by%20region.pdf{{dead link|date=December 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }} accessed 21 February 2012</ref>\n\nQualifications at the secondary school and [[post-secondary education|post-secondary]] ([[further education]]) level are provided by the [[Scottish Qualifications Authority]], which is the national awarding and accrediting body in Scotland, and delivered through various schools, colleges and other centres. Political responsibility for education at all levels is vested in the [[Scottish Parliament]] and the [[Learning and Justice Directorates|Learning Directorate]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.scotland.gov.uk/About/People/Directorates/learning |title=About: People: Learning Directorate |publisher=Scottish Government |accessdate=25 August 2014 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140826160941/http://www.scotland.gov.uk/About/People/Directorates/learning |archivedate=26 August 2014 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> Inspections and audits of educational standards are conducted by three bodies: [[Care Inspectorate (Scotland)|Care Inspectorate]] inspects [[Social care in Scotland|care standards]] in pre-school provision; Education Scotland (formerly [[Her Majesty's Inspectorate of Education]]) for [[pre-school]], primary, [[secondary education|education]], [[further education|further]] and [[adult education|community]] education; with the Scottish office of the [[Quality Assurance Agency for Higher Education]] (QAA Scotland) responsible for higher education.\n\nIn 2014, research by the [[Office for National Statistics]] found that Scotland was the most highly educated country in Europe and among the most well-educated in the world in terms of tertiary education attainment, above countries like [[Finland]], Ireland and [[Luxembourg]], with roughly 40% of Scots aged 16\u201364 educated to [[National Vocational Qualification#Levels|NVQ level 4]] and above.<ref>{{cite news |title=Scotland 'most highly educated country in Europe' |author=ITV |url=http://www.itv.com/news/update/2014-06-05/scotland-most-well-educated-country-in-europe/ |accessdate=8 June 2014 |date=5 June 2014 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140607235349/http://www.itv.com/news/update/2014-06-05/scotland-most-well-educated-country-in-europe/ |archivedate=7 June 2014 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n==History==\n{{main|History of education in Scotland}}\n\n==Stages of compulsory education==\n[[File:Adam Ingram (2497280178).jpg|thumb|right|Pupils and Early Years Minister [[Adam Ingram (SNP politician)|Adam Ingram]], Education and Lifelong Learning Secretary [[Fiona Hyslop]] and Schools and Skills Minister [[Maureen Watt]] with pupils at Avenue End Primary Campus in Glasgow.]]\nChildren start primary school aged between 4\u00bd and 5\u00bd depending on when the child's birthday falls.<ref name=\"FAQs\">{{cite web |url=http://www.scotland.gov.uk/Topics/Education/Schools/FAQs |title=Frequently Asked Questions |publisher=Scottish Government |date=19 December 2013 |accessdate=24 August 2014 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140819035352/http://www.scotland.gov.uk/Topics/Education/Schools/FAQs |archivedate=19 August 2014 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> Scottish school policy places all those born between March of a given year and February of the following year in the same year group. Children born between March and August start school in August at between 5 and 5\u00bd years old, and those born between September and February start school in the previous August at between age 4\u00bd and 4 years 11 months years old. The Scottish system is the most flexible in the UK, however, as parents of children born between September and December can decide to defer for 1 year (but may or may not receive a funded nursery place in the deferral year), whilst children born between January and February can opt to hold their child back a year and let them start school the following August, with guaranteed nursery funding. This usually allows those not ready for formal education to have an extra year at an early years centre (formerly known as nursery).\n\nPupils remain at primary school for seven years. Then aged eleven or twelve, they start secondary school for a compulsory four years with the following two years being optional. In Scotland, pupils sit National 4/5 exams (previously [[Standard Grade]] or [[Intermediate exams]]) at the age of fifteen/sixteen, normally for between 6 and eight subjects including compulsory exams in English and Mathematics. A Science subject (Physics, Biology or Chemistry) and a Social Subject (Geography, History or Modern Studies) were also compulsory, but this was changed in accordance with the new curriculum. It is now required by the Scottish Parliament for students to have two hours of physical education a week; each school may vary these compulsory combinations. The school leaving age is generally sixteen (after completion of National 4/5s), after which students may choose to remain at school and study for [[Higher (Scottish)|Higher]] and/or [[Advanced Higher (Scottish)|Advanced Higher]] exams.\n\nA small number of students at certain private, [[Independent school (UK)|independent schools]] may follow the [[Education in England|English system]] and study towards [[General Certificate of Secondary Education|GCSE]] instead of National 4/5s (Standard Grades), and towards [[GCE Advanced Level|A and AS-Levels]] instead of (or alongside) Higher Grade and Advanced Higher exams. The [[International Baccalaureate]] has also been introduced in some independent schools.\n\nThe table below lists rough equivalences with the year system in the rest of the United Kingdom (For England and Wales, the equivalence given is for children born before 1 September; the equivalence for those born from September to February [December for deferred pupils] is given in brackets):\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! Scotland\n! Age at start of school year\n! Age at end of school year\n! England and Wales\n! Northern Ireland\n|-\n! Playgroup\n|2-3|| 3-4 || Nursery || Play School\n|-\n!Nursery \n|3-4|| 4-5 \n|Reception || Nursery\n|-\n! Primary 1\n|4-5||5-6|| Year 1 || P1\n|-\n! Primary 2\n|5-6||6-7|| Year 2 || P2\n|-\n! Primary 3\n|6-7||7-8|| Year 3 || P3\n|-\n! Primary 4\n|7-8||8-9|| Year 4 || P4\n|-\n! Primary 5\n|8-9||9-10|| Year 5 || P5\n|-\n! Primary 6\n|9-10||10-11|| Year 6 || P6\n|-\n! Primary 7\n|10-11||11-12|| Year 7 || P7\n|-\n! S1 ([[First year]])\n|11-12||12-13|| Year 8 || Year 8 (1st Year)\n|-\n! S2 ([[Second year]])\n|12-13||13-14|| Year 9|| Year 9 (2nd Year)\n|-\n! S3 ([[Third year]])\n|13-14||14-15|| Year 10 || Year 10 (3rd Year)\n|-\n! S4 ([[Fourth year]])\n|14-15||15-16|| Year 11 || Year 11 (4th Year)\n|-\n! S5 ([[Fifth year]])\n|15-16||16-17|| Year 12 (Lower Sixth Form)\n|| Year 12 (5th Year)\n|-\n! S6 ([[Sixth form#Scotland|Sixth Year]])\n|16-17||17-18|| Year 13 (Upper Sixth Form) || Year 13 (L6th Year)\n|-\n|\n|17-18\n|18-19\n|\n|Year 14 (U6th Year)\n|}\n\n===Access to early years centres, primary and secondary school===\n\nGovernment funded schools are free for children aged 5\u201319.<ref name=\"UK Council\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ukcisa.org.uk/student/accommodation_health.php|title=UKCISA - international student advice and guidance|website=www.ukcisa.org.uk|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120911115643/http://www.ukcisa.org.uk/student/accommodation_health.php|archivedate=11 September 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref> In many cases, this applies to children of international post-graduate students,<ref name=\"British Council\">{{cite web |url=http://www.britishcouncil.org/learning-infosheets-choosing-state-funded-schools.pdf |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2012-09-10 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130503154102/http://www.britishcouncil.org/learning-infosheets-choosing-state-funded-schools.pdf |archivedate=3 May 2013 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> and other immigrants.\n\nThe age ranges specify the youngest age for a child entering that year and the oldest age for a child leaving that year. Playgroup can be described as a daycare centre for toddlers, then children may go on to attend an early years centre as soon as they have passed their third birthday, and progress to Primary 1 in the August of the year in which they turn five. \n\nIn general, the cut-off point for ages is the end of February, so all children must be of a certain age on 1 March to begin class in August. \n\nAll parents of children born between September and February (i.e. still 4 years old on the school start date) are entitled to defer entry to Primary School if they believe their child is not ready for school.\n\nOnly children whose birthdays fall in January or February will be considered for funding for a subsequent year at an early years centre, unless there are special circumstances.\n\nChildren may leave school once they reach their statutory school leaving date; this is dependent on date of birth.  For children born between 1 March and 30 September, this date is 31 May of their 4th year of secondary school.  For children born between 1 October and 28 February, the last day of June is the first date they may leave school if they have a placement at college and the school have signed the health & safety forms.\n\nWhich high school the children go to depends on the area where they live, known as the \"[[catchment area]]\", which has a specific high school that takes children who live in that area.\n\nParents can also apply for a placement request if they would like their child to attend a school outside their catchment area and a panel will decide if the child is the most worthy (out of all placing requests) to take one of the spaces left after all children from the catchment area have been taken.\n\nThe table below lists list the numbers of children, schools and teachers in all publicly funded schools:<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.scotland.gov.uk/Resource/0044/00443414.pdf |title=Summary Statistics for Schools in Scotland, No.4 \u00a6 2013 Edition |publisher=Scottish Government |date=11 February 2014 |accessdate=25 August 2014}}</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!\n! Children\n! Schools\n! Teachers\n! pupil:teacher ratio\n|-\n! Early Years Education\n|  102,871 || 2,504 || 1,288 || \n|-\n! Primary\n|  377,372 || 2,056 || 22,905 || 16.5\n|-\n! Secondary\n|  289,164 || 364 || 23,695 || 12.2\n|-\n! Special\n|  6,984 || 149 || 2,020 || 3.5\n|-\n|}\n\n[[Home education in the United Kingdom|Home education]] is also legal in Scotland. Parents wishing to home educate do not need the permission of the Local Authority unless the children are already registered at a school. There are no exact numbers available for children being educated at home in Scotland.<ref>[http://www.educationscotland.gov.uk/parentzone/yourchildatschool/choosingaschool/homeeducation/index.asp Education Scotland, Home Education] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141001153601/http://www.educationscotland.gov.uk/parentzone/yourchildatschool/choosingaschool/homeeducation/index.asp |date=1 October 2014 }}</ref>\n\n==Governance==\n\nWithin the [[Scottish Government]], the [[Cabinet Secretary for Education and Skills]] has overall responsibility for education provision in Scotland. The Cabinet Secretary is assisted by three junior ministers, currently the [[Minister for Childcare and Early Years]], the [[Minister for Further Education, Higher Education and Science]] and the [[Minister for Employability and Training]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://beta.gov.scot/about/who-runs-government/cabinet-and-ministers/cabinet-secretary-education-skills/|title=Cabinet Secretary for Education and Skills - gov.scot|website=beta.gov.scot|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170912055234/https://beta.gov.scot/about/who-runs-government/cabinet-and-ministers/cabinet-secretary-education-skills/|archivedate=12 September 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref> \n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! colspan= 4 | Cabinet Secretaries and Ministers overseeing Education in Scotland\n|-\n! Portfolio\n! Minister\n!! class=\"unsortable\" | Image\n! Areas of Responsibility\n|- \n| [[Cabinet Secretary for Education and Skills]] <br/> <small>(also serving as [[Deputy First Minister of Scotland]])</small>\n| data-sort-value=\"Sturgeon\" | [[John Swinney]] {{small|[[Member of the Scottish Parliament|MSP]]}}\n| [[File:John Swinney, Deputy First Minister.png|85px]]\n| School Standards <br/> Quality and Improvement <br/> School Infrastructures and Staffing <br/> Educational Attainment <br/> Qualifications <br/> Teaching profession <br/> Behaviour and anti-bullying measures <br/> Named Person and Looked After policies <br/> Youth Work <br/> Early Years Education <br/> Children's Services <br/> Children's hearing \n|-\n| [[Minister for Childcare and Early Years]]\n| data-sort-value=\"McDonald\" | [[Maree Todd]] {{small|MSP}}\n| [[File:Maree Todd MSP - May 2016.jpg|85px]]\n| Adoption and fostering <br/> Early Years <br/> Childcare <br/> Child Protection <br/> Children's Rights <br/> Looked After Children <br/> Protection of Vulnerable Groups <br/> Social Services Workforce \n|-\n| [[Minister for Further Education, Higher Education and Science]]\n| [[Richard Lochhead]] {{small|MSP}}\n| [[File:RichardLochhead MSP.jpg|85px]]\n| Further education <br/> Colleges <br/> Universities <br/> Student Funding <br/> STEM Subjects <br/> Widening access \n|}\n\n\n==Qualifications framework==\n[[File:Kilmarnock Academy complex.jpg|thumb|right|[[Kilmarnock Academy]] is the only school in Scotland to have educated two [[Nobel Prize]] Laureates<ref>[[List of Nobel laureates by secondary school affiliation]]</ref><ref>https://newsnet.scot/archive/scotlands-top-school-for-nobel-prize-winners/</ref>]]\n\nAll educational qualifications in Scotland are part of the [[Scottish Credit and Qualifications Framework]], ranging between [[Scottish Qualifications Authority]] qualifications, [[Scottish Vocational Qualification]]s and higher education qualifications. \n\n'''Progression in Qualifications'''\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! S4\n! S5\n! S6\n|-\n| National 3\n|  National 4  ||  National 5\n|-\n| National 4\n|  National 5  ||  Higher\n|-\n| National 5\n|  Higher  ||  Advanced Higher\n|}\n\nThe vast majority of Scottish pupils take [[Scottish Qualifications Certificate]] qualifications provided by the [[Scottish Qualifications Authority]] (SQA). Generally, most pupils take National 4/5s (previously [[Standard Grade]]s, but some schools offered Intermediates instead) in S3-S4, and [[Higher (Scottish)|Highers]] in S5. The number of National 4/5 qualifications a pupil enters can vary drastically depending on the individual, with the most common number of National 5s taken, per pupil, in 2017 being 6,<ref>https://www.sqa.org.uk/sqa/files_ccc/ASR2017_National5.xls</ref> however some may choose to undertake as few as one or two, or as many as eight or nine. For those who wish to remain at school for the final year (S6), more Highers and [[Advanced Higher]]s (formerly [[CSYS]]) in S6 can be taken. Previous qualifications [[Intermediate 1]] and [[Intermediate 2]] \u2013 were intended to be roughly equivalent to General and Credit Level Standard Grades respectively.\n\nPupils can go to university at the end of S5, as Highers provide the entry requirements for Scottish universities where degrees are normally four years long; however, recently it is more common for students to remain until S6, taking further Highers and/or taking Advanced Highers. The majority of English universities, the most popular choice for Scottish students who wish to study university degrees outside of Scotland, require Advanced Higher qualification levels as these are deemed by the English universities to be most similar to A-levels.\n\n==Secondary schools==\n\nSecondary education is provided by a number of [[secondary school]]s throughout Scotland, both in the state and independent sector. The vast majority of schools in the state sector are administered directly by the local Education Authority, which is synonymous with the 32 councils used for local government. <ref>Section 123 of the Local Government (Scotland) Act 1973</ref>\n\nThere are three broad classifications of schools in Scotland<ref>[https://researchbriefings.parliament.uk/ResearchBriefing/Summary/CBP-7819 House of Commons Library - Schools in Scotland]</ref>: \n\n* '''State-funded schools''': These are schools under the management of an education authority. Theses schools do not charge fees to attend and have no entrance restrictions. Both denominational and non-denominational schools fall within this category. In the Education (Scotland) Act 1980 they are also referred to as 'public schools' (not to be confused with the other meaning of [[Public school (United Kingdom)|public school]] in the United Kingdom.\n\n* '''Grant-Aided schools''': Grant-Aided schools are independent of their education authority and can decide on their own governance, but are directly funded by the [[Scottish Government|Scottish Ministers]]. There is one mainstream Grant-Aided school in Scotland, [[Jordanhill School]], formerly linked to [[Jordanhill College of Education]]. The remaining seven Grant-Aided schools are [[special schools]], which are Capability Scotland: Corseford School, Capability Scotland: Stanmore House School, [[Donaldson's School]], East Park School, Harmeny School, the [[Royal Blind School]] and the Scottish Centre for Children with Motor Impairments (Craighalbert Centre). Despite their status, several of these schools are members of the [[Scottish Council of Independent Schools]].\n\n* '''Independent schools''': Independent schools are schools that are not under management of an education authority and do not receive direct state funding. To qualify as a school, it must provide full-time education for at least five pupils of school age. Schools of this type are required to register and are subject to inspections by [[Education Scotland|Her Majesty's inspectors]]. Most are members of the [[Scottish Council of Independent Schools]]. One independent school, [[St Mary's Music School]], receives Aided Places (similar to the abolished [[Assisted Places Scheme]]) where fees can be paid by the Scottish Ministers.\n\n===School naming=== \n[[File:Marr College, Troon.jpg|thumb|right|[[Marr College]] in [[Troon]], [[South Ayrshire]], carries the name College rather than High School or Academy]]\nThere is not a set name for secondary schools in Scotland, but whatever they might be called, with just a few specific exceptions in mainly rural or island authorities, state secondary schools in Scotland are fully [[Comprehensive school|comprehensive]] and non-selective. Amongst the state-run secondary schools:\n\n* 188 are nominally ''High Schools''. These are spread across the country. Almost all Catholic secondaries are high schools, with the majority of the other names being non-denominational schools. For example, in West Dunbartonshire, the non-denominational schools are Vale of Leven, Dumbarton, and Clydebank Academies while the Catholic schools are Our Lady & Saint Patrick's High School and St Peter the Apostle's High School.\n* 131 are nominally ''Academies''. These are spread across the country but are in high concentration in North-East Scotland and Ayrshire, an example is [[Banchory Academy]]. There are also three Royal Academies, in [[Irvine, North Ayrshire]]; [[Tain]]; and [[Inverness]].\n* 15 are nominally ''Secondary Schools'' (colloquially abbreviated to \"secondaries\").\n* 14 are nominally ''Grammar Schools''. Most of these schools were defined as [[grammar schools]] under a previous (now dissolved) system but their names remain. Popular areas for grammar schools are [[Argyll and Bute]], East Lothian and [[South Lanarkshire]].\n* 13 are simply ''Schools''. These schools cater for Primary as well as Secondary school children. They are found in rural areas or islands.\n* 8 are ''Junior High Schools''. These schools are found exclusively in the [[Orkney]] and [[Shetland]] Islands. They cater for school children from P1 to S4.\n* 4 are ''Colleges''. These include [[Madras College]] (in [[St Andrews]], Fife), [[Marr College]] (in [[Troon]], [[South Ayrshire]]) and [[St Joseph's College, Dumfries|St Joseph's College]] (in [[Dumfries]], [[Dumfries and Galloway]]).\n\nOther schools include The Community School of Auchterarder, [[Auchterarder]], [[Perth and Kinross]]; The Nicolson Institute, [[Stornoway]], [[Western Isles]]; North Walls Community School on [[Hoy]], [[Orkney Islands]] and Wester Hailes Education Centre, [[Wester Hailes]], Edinburgh. All of these are, equally, fully comprehensive non-selective schools, differing only in designation from all other state secondary schools in Scotland.\n\n==School provision==\n\n===National Curriculum===\n{{Main|Curriculum for Excellence}}\nIn 2003, work began on an education reform programme, to produce a new ''[[Curriculum for Excellence]]'' that would replace existing guidance on the school curriculum.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.educationscotland.gov.uk/thecurriculum/whatiscurriculumforexcellence/howwasthecurriculumdeveloped/processofchange/timeline.asp |title=How was the curriculum developed: Process of change: Timeline About Curriculum for Excellence |publisher=Education Scotland |accessdate=24 August 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140826113301/http://www.educationscotland.gov.uk/thecurriculum/whatiscurriculumforexcellence/howwasthecurriculumdeveloped/processofchange/timeline.asp |archivedate=26 August 2014 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> Curriculum for Excellence was launched in Scottish secondary schools from school session 2012\u20132013.\n\nIn 2017, new reforms were introduced moving control over curriculum and schools more towards head teachers and parents.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.scotsman.com/news/politics/snp-and-tories-back-john-swinney-s-school-reforms-1-4489307|title=SNP and Tories back John Swinney\u2019s school reforms|website=www.scotsman.com|language=en|access-date=2017-07-22|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170628201324/http://www.scotsman.com/news/politics/snp-and-tories-back-john-swinney-s-school-reforms-1-4489307|archivedate=28 June 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n===Religion in schools===\nThe vast majority of schools are non-[[Religious denomination|denominational]], and include the parish schools, pioneered by the Church of Scotland and other Protestant Churches, which became state schools in 1872. Religious education is taught in non-denominational schools and in denominational schools. Of over 2,500 schools in Scotland, there are 366 state schools which are Roman Catholic, three Episcopalian and one Jewish. The [[Education (Scotland) Act 1918]] brought Roman Catholic schools within the State education system, ensuring the promotion of a Roman Catholic ethos within such schools.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gov.scot/Topics/Education/Schools/FAQs|title=Frequently Asked Questions|first=Scottish Government, St. Andrew's House, Regent Road, Edinburgh EH1 3DG Tel:0131 556 8400|last=ceu@scotland.gsi.gov.uk|date=1 April 2003|website=www.gov.scot|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150721174221/http://www.gov.scot/Topics/Education/Schools/FAQs|archivedate=21 July 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n\n==Attainment==\n\nIn 2015, the Scottish Government launched the Scottish Attainment Challenge which aims to achieve equity in educational outcomes throughout Scotland. The Scottish Government envisages equity being achieved by ensuring every child has the same opportunity to succeed, with a particular focus on closing the poverty-related attainment gap. It is underpinned by national Scottish educational policies such as [[Curriculum for Excellence]], Getting it Right for Every Child (GIRFEC) as well as the National Improvement Framework.<ref name=\"gov.scot\">{{cite web|url=http://www.gov.scot/Topics/Education/Schools/Raisingeducationalattainment|title=Schools: Pupil attainment: closing the gap - gov.scot|website=www.gov.scot|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170912055204/http://www.gov.scot/Topics/Education/Schools/Raisingeducationalattainment|archivedate=12 September 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The attainment challenge focuses and accelerates targeted improvement activity in literacy, numeracy and health and wellbeing in specific areas of Scotland, known as \"challenge authorities\" (those councils with a higher percentage of children growing up in poverty and deprivation). At a cost of \u00a3750 million to the Scottish Government through the Attainment Scotland Fund, the challenge is a targeted initiative focused on supporting pupils in the local authorities of Scotland with the highest concentrations of deprivation. Currently, the nine 'Challenge Authorities' are [[Glasgow City Council]], [[Dundee City Council]], [[Inverclyde]], [[West Dunbartonshire]], [[North Ayrshire]], [[Clackmannanshire]], [[North Lanarkshire]], [[East Ayrshire]] and [[Renfrewshire]]<ref name=\"gov.scot\"/>.\n\nOn 1 February 2017 the share each primary and secondary school will receive for the academic year 2017\u20132018 from the Scottish Government's \u00a3120 million Pupil Equity Funding was announced by the Deputy First Minister and Cabinet Secretary for Education and Skills [[John Swinney]].  This funding is provided through the Attainment Scotland Fund and allocated directly to schools, targeted at those children most affected by the poverty related attainment gap<ref name=\"gov.scot\"/>.\n\n===Music education===\n[[Music education]] is available at several levels. Formal music education begins at 4\u00bd years and can progress as high as postgraduate studies. Music education can take place within a [[Music schools in Scotland|Scottish Music school]]; through a music service or privately.\n\n===Scottish Gaelic medium education===\n{{main|Gaelic medium education in Scotland}}\nSome schools in Scotland provide education given in the [[Scottish Gaelic]] language. They are mainly located in the main cities of Scotland and in areas with higher amounts of Gaelic speakers. Gaelic medium education is becoming increasingly popular throughout Scotland, and the number of pupils who are in Gaelic medium education at primary school level has risen from 24 in 1985, to 2500 in the 2012\u201313 school year.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.gaidhlig.org.uk/bord/en/our-work/gaelic-education/ |title=Our Work: Gaelic education |publisher=Bord na Gaidhlig |accessdate=12 April 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150412150711/http://www.gaidhlig.org.uk/bord/en/our-work/gaelic-education/ |archivedate=12 April 2015 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n==Further education==\n[[File:City of Glasgow College riverside Campus DSCN1856.jpg|thumb|[[City of Glasgow College]]'s Riverside Campus]]\n{{Main|List of further education colleges in Scotland}}\n[[Further education]] is provided through a network of [[further education colleges]] available to people having reached the end of compulsory education at 16. In the early 2010s, a number of colleges were merged to form larger, regional institutions. \n\nColleges offer a wide range of vocational qualifications to young people and older adults, including vocational, competency-based qualifications (previously known as [[NVQ|SVQ]]s), [[Higher National Certificates]] and [[Higher National Diplomas]]. In Scotland, FE college students receiving certain qualifications - frequently HNC and HND qualifications in a relevant subject - can apply for entry at a later stage at university. \n\nFurther education colleges also provide support to [[apprenticeship]] programmes, which are coordinated by the public body [[Skills Development Scotland]].\n\n==Higher Education==\n{{Main|Universities in Scotland}}\n{{See also|List of Universities in Scotland}}\n[[File:Queen Margaret University main building.jpg|thumb|right|The Main Building of [[Queen Margaret University]]]]\nThere are fifteen universities in Scotland and three other institutions of higher education which have the authority to award [[academic degrees]].<ref name=uniscot>{{cite web |url=http://www.universities-scotland.ac.uk/index.php?page=briefing |title=Briefing |publisher=Universities Scotland |accessdate=1 April 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110723071847/http://www.universities-scotland.ac.uk/index.php?page=briefing |archivedate=23 July 2011 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> The oldest is [[University of St Andrews|St. Andrews]], which was founded in 1413. Three other \"[[Ancient universities of Scotland|ancient universities]]\", [[University of Glasgow|Glasgow]], [[University of Aberdeen|Aberdeen]] and [[University of Edinburgh|Edinburgh]], date from before 1600.<ref>M. Gardiner, ''Modern Scottish Culture'' (Edinburgh: Edinburgh University Press, 2005), {{ISBN|0748620273}}, p. 83.</ref> The [[University of the Highlands and Islands]] (UHI) gained full university status in 2011, having been created through the federation of 13 colleges and research institutions across the Highlands and Islands, a process that began in 2001.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.highland.gov.uk/news/article/2239/uhi_is_awarded_taught_degree_awarding_powers |title=UHI is awarded taught degree awarding powers |publisher=Highland Council |date=26 June 2008 |accessdate=29 June 2014 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140714193338/http://www.highland.gov.uk/news/article/2239/uhi_is_awarded_taught_degree_awarding_powers |archivedate=14 July 2014 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nAll Scottish universities have the power to award degrees at all levels: undergraduate, taught postgraduate, and doctoral. Education in Scotland is controlled by the [[Scottish Government]] under the terms of the [[Scotland Act 1998]]. The minister responsible for higher education is the [[Cabinet Secretary for Education and Lifelong Learning]], currently [[Angela Constance|Angela Constance MSP]] of the [[Scottish National Party]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.gov.scot/About/People/Ministers/Cabinet-Secretary-for-Education-and-Lifelong-Learn |title=Cabinet Secretary for Education & Lifelong Learning: Angela Constance MSP |publisher=[[Scottish Government]] |accessdate=12 April 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150405185559/http://www.gov.scot/About/People/Ministers/Cabinet-Secretary-for-Education-and-Lifelong-Learn |archivedate=5 April 2015 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> University status in Scotland and throughout the United Kingdom today is conferred by the [[Her Majesty's Most Honourable Privy Council|Privy Council]] which takes advice from the [[Quality Assurance Agency for Higher Education]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.parliament.uk/commons/lib/research/briefings/snpc-3708.pdf |title=The Privy Council, Standard Note: SN/PC/3708 |date=5 July 2005 |publisher=The Privy Council |pages=5\u20136 |accessdate=6 July 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111227183508/http://www.parliament.uk/commons/lib/research/briefings/snpc-3708.pdf |archivedate=27 December 2011 }}</ref><ref name=QAA>{{cite web |url=http://www.qaa.ac.uk/assuring-standards-and-quality/daput |title=Degree-awarding powers and university title |publisher=[[Quality Assurance Agency for Higher Education]] (QAA) |date=29 November 2012 |accessdate=26 July 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140810142933/http://www.qaa.ac.uk/assuring-standards-and-quality/daput |archivedate=10 August 2014 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nAll Scottish universities are [[public universities]] and funded by the [[Scottish Government]] (through its [[Scottish Funding Council]]<ref name=scotgov>{{cite web |url=http://www.scotland.gov.uk/Topics/Education/UniversitiesColleges/16640 |publisher=The Scottish Government |title=Education and Training: Universities and Colleges: Universities |date=16 July 2014 |accessdate=25 August 2014 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140830045609/http://www.scotland.gov.uk/Topics/Education/UniversitiesColleges/16640 |archivedate=30 August 2014 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>) and financial support is provided for Scottish-domiciled students by the [[Student Awards Agency for Scotland]]. Students ordinarily resident in Scotland or the [[European Union]] do not pay [[tuition fees]] for their first undergraduate degree, but tuition fees are charged for those from the rest of the United Kingdom. All students are required to pay tuition fees for postgraduate education (e.g. MSc, PhD), except in certain priority areas funded by the Scottish Government, or if another source of funding can be found (e.g. [[research council]] studentship for a PhD). A representative body called [[Universities Scotland]] works to promote Scotland's universities, as well as six other higher education institutions.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.universities-scotland.ac.uk/ |title=Universities Scotland |accessdate=7 September 2010 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100211100535/http://www.universities-scotland.ac.uk/ |archivedate=11 February 2010 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nThe university sector in Scotland had a total income of \u00a33.5 billion in 2014/15 with the Scottish Government giving approximately \u00a3623 million in funding for individual university student support. The Scottish Funding Council contributing \u00a31.1 billion of public money to the fifteen universities, this was a six per cent reduction since 2010/11.<ref name=\"Audit of Scottish universities\">{{cite web |url=http://www.audit-scotland.gov.uk/uploads/docs/report/2016/nr_160707_higher_education.pdf |title=Audit of higher education in Scottish universities |access-date=18 November 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161119064422/http://www.audit-scotland.gov.uk/uploads/docs/report/2016/nr_160707_higher_education.pdf |archivedate=19 November 2016 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n[[File:St Andrews gowns.jpg|thumbnail|right|St Andrews students in undergraduate gowns]]\nIn 2014\u201315, approximately 232,570 students studied at universities or institutes of higher education in Scotland, of which 56% were female and 44% male, with 66% being domiciled in Scotland, 12% from the rest of the United Kingdom, 9% from the EU and the remaining 13% being [[international students]]. Of all these, approximately 76% were studying for their first degree (i.e. undergraduate level) and 24% for a taught postgraduate degree (primarily a master's degree) or a doctoral research degree (primarily PhD). The remainder were mostly on other programmes such as [[Higher National Diploma]].<ref name=\"Audit of Scottish universities\" /> 16,000 students were studying in Scotland with [[The Open University]] via distance-learning, and the Open University teaches 40 per cent of Scotland's part-time undergraduates.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www3.open.ac.uk/near-you/scotland//index.asp |title=The Open University in Scotland |accessdate=6 July 2010 |publisher=The Open University |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100405092500/http://www3.open.ac.uk/near-you/scotland/index.asp |archivedate=5 April 2010 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nIn the 2019 [[QS World University Rankings]], three Scottish universities are among the top 100 worldwide: [[University of Edinburgh]] (at 18), [[University of Glasgow]] (at 69), [[University of St. Andrews]] (at 97). Other high ranked universities are the [[University of Aberdeen]] (at 172), [[University of Strathclyde]] (at 268), [[University of Dundee]] (at 272), [[Heriot-Watt University]] (at 302) and [[University of Stirling]] (at 417).<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.topuniversities.com/university-rankings/world-university-rankings/2019 |title=QS World University Rankings 2019 |access-date=11 May 2019}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of schools in Scotland]]\n* [[List of independent schools in Scotland]]\n* [[Home education in the United Kingdom]]\n* [[Music schools in Scotland]]\n* [[Aedips|Association of Educational Development and Improvement Professionals]]\n* [[List of further education colleges in Scotland]]\n* [[Her Majesty's Inspectorate of Education]] ([[Scotland]])\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.scotland.gov.uk/library5/education/etsnd4-03.asp Silicon Glen, Scotland \u2013 Intro to Scottish Education]\n\n{{Scotland topics}}\n{{Education in Europe}}\n{{Education in the United Kingdom}}\n{{Scottish education}}\n\n[[Category:Education in Scotland| ]]\n[[Category:Secondary education by country|Scotland]]\n[[Category:Public bodies of the Scottish Government]]\n[[Category:Scottish Government Learning and Justice Directorate]]\n", "name_user": "86.20.221.243", "label": "vandal", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eAccess to early years centres, primary and secondary school:Added content)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Education_in_Scotland"}
{"title_page": "Derek Sloan", "text_new": "{{pp-semi|small=yes}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific-prefix = \n| name             =Derek Sloan\n| honorific-suffix = {{post-nominals|country=CAN|MP|size=100%}}\n| image            = Dereksloan2110.jpg\n| imagesize        = \n| riding           = [[Hastings\u2014Lennox and Addington]]\n| parliament       = Canadian\n| term_start       = October 21, 2019\n| term_end         =\n| predecessor      =[[Mike Bossio]]\n| successor        =\n| birth_date       = {{Birth date and age|1984|11|11}}\n| birth_place      = [[Norfolk County, Ontario]], Canada\n| death_date       =\n| death_place      =\n| profession       = Lawyer\n| party            = [[Conservative Party of Canada|Conservative]]\n| residence        = \n| footnotes        = \n| spouse           = \n| children= \n|}}\n\n'''Derek Sloan''' {{post-nominals|country=CAN|MP}} (born November 11, 1984) is a [[Canadians|Canadian]] politician who was elected to represent the [[electoral district (Canada)|riding]] of [[Hastings\u2014Lennox and Addington]] in the [[House of Commons of Canada]] in the [[2019 Canadian federal election]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Canada election results: Hastings-Lennox and Addington|url=https://globalnews.ca/news/5760824/canada-election-hastings-lennox-and-addington/|date=October 21, 2019|publisher=Global News|accessdate=October 21, 2019}}</ref> He is the first [[Seventh-day Adventist Church|Seventh-day Adventist]] ever elected to the [[Canadian House of Commons]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Interview With Derek Sloan, First Adventist Elected to Canada\u2019s Parliament|url=https://www.nadadventist.org/news/interview-derek-sloan-first-adventist-elected-canadas-parliament|date=December 11, 2019|publisher=North American Division of the Seventh-day Adventist Church|accessdate=December 18, 2019}}</ref> Sloan is running as a candidate for the [[2020 Conservative Party of Canada leadership election|leadership of the Conservative Party of Canada]], and has gained notoriety for his controversial views on LGBT issues.<ref>{{cite web|title=Being gay is not a choice but who cares if it is?|url=https://www.thestar.com/opinion/star-columnists/2020/01/29/being-gay-is-not-a-choice-but-who-cares-if-it-is.html|date=April 4, 2020|publisher=Toronto Star|accessdate=April 11, 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Background ==\nSloan was born in 1984 and raised near [[Waterford, Ontario|Waterford]] in Ontario.<ref>{{cite web|title=Team Member: Derek Sloan|url=https://www.conservative.ca/team-member/derek-sloan/|date=August 12, 2018|publisher=Conservative Party of Canada|accessdate=April 11, 2020}}</ref> He attended [[Kingsway College]], a private [[Seventh-day Adventist]] highschool in [[Oshawa]].<ref>{{cite journal |title=Congratulations |journal=KC Contact |date=Spring 2014 |page=14 |url=https://static1.squarespace.com/static/58af1200f7e0ab64d5e083d0/t/59808c5620099ecf2e5c7041/1501596794725/KC%2BContact%2BSpring%2B2014%2BEdition.pdf |accessdate=27 December 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn 2003, Sloan enrolled at [[Pacific Union College|Pacific Union College (PUC)]], a private university in [[Napa Valley AVA|Napa Valley]], [[California]] associated with the [[Seventh-day Adventist Church]]. There he completed a bachelor degree in business in 2007.<ref>{{cite web|title=Candidates: Derek Sloan|url=https://www.insideottawavalley.com/ottawavalley-news/federal-election/vote-2019/candidates/17212|date=October 20, 2019|publisher=InsideOttawaValley.com|accessdate=April 11, 2020}}</ref> While attending PUC, Sloan served as President of the university's Student Association in 2007.<ref>{{cite web|title=Candidates: Derek Sloan|url=https://www.insideottawavalley.com/ottawavalley-news/federal-election/vote-2019/candidates/17212|date=October 20, 2019|publisher=InsideOttawaValley.com|accessdate=April 11, 2020}}</ref>\n\nAfter graduating, Sloan moved to [[Toronto|Toronto, Ontario]] to work at a water-fuel systems company.<ref>{{cite web|title=325 PUC graduates celebrate with faith, flying tortillas|url=https://napavalleyregister.com/community/star/news/local/puc-graduates-celebrate-with-faith-flying-tortillas/article_29488f5e-3382-5351-b75f-01cee2e27a33.html|date=June 21, 2007|publisher=Napa Valley Register|accessdate=April 11, 2020}}</ref> Then, between 2011 and 2014 he ran Sloan's Furniture Liquidation in [[Oshawa]]. In 2014, Sloan began a law degree at [[Queen's University at Kingston|Queen's University]] in [[Kingston, Ontario]], and he finished articling in 2018. Sloan has said he pursued law because he was interested in \"defending religious liberties against political correctness.\"<ref>{{cite web|title=INTERVIEW WITH DEREK SLOAN, FIRST ADVENTIST ELECTED TO CANADA\u2019S PARLIAMENT|url=https://news.eud.adventist.org/en/all-news/news/go/2019-12-12/interview-with-derek-sloan-first-adventist-elected-to-canadas-parliament/|date=December 12, 2019|publisher=Seventh-day Adventist Church|accessdate=April 11, 2020}}</ref>\n\nSloan is married to his wife Jennifer, and they have two daughters, Fiona and Nora, and a son Callum.<ref>{{cite web|title=Team Member: Derek Sloan|url=https://www.conservative.ca/team-member/derek-sloan/|date=August 12, 2018|publisher=Conservative Party of Canada|accessdate=April 11, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Political Career==\n\n===2019 Federal Election===\nIn 2018, Sloan announced that he would seek the [[Conservative Party of Canada]] nomination for the riding of [[Hastings\u2014Lennox and Addington]], despite having only recently moved to the riding.<ref>{{cite web|title=Four candidates for HL&A Conservative race|url=https://www.quintenews.com/2018/11/14/4-candidates-in-the-conservative-race-for-hla/|date=November 14, 2018|publisher=Quinte News|accessdate=April 11, 2020}}</ref> At the nomination meeting, Sloan defeated three other candidates: a City Councillor who had served for fifteen years in [[Belleville, Ontario|Belleville]], a lawyer who had lived in the area for twenty years, and a local business owner.<ref>{{cite web|title=Sloan selected as new Conservative candidate in federal election|url=https://inquinte.ca/story/sloan-selected-as-new-conservative-candidate-in-federal-election|date=November 14, 2018|publisher=In Quinte News|accessdate=December 8, 2018}}</ref> Sloan would go on to defeat [[Liberal Party of Canada|Liberal]] incumbent [[Mike Bossio]] in the [[2019 Canadian Federal Election|2019 Federal Election]].\n\n===2020 Conservative Party Leadership Election===\nSloan announced his candidacy for the [[2020 Conservative Party of Canada leadership election]] on 22 January 2020.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/DerekSloanCPC/status/1220012199042670592?ref_src=twsrc%5Etfw%7Ctwcamp%5Etweetembed%7Ctwterm%5E1220022905045749766&ref_url=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.ctvnews.ca%2Fpolitics%2Frookie-mp-derek-sloan-says-he-s-running-for-conservative-leadership-1.4778567|title=I'm in. It's time to stop being afraid to be conservative. Stay tuned...|first=Derek|last=Sloan|date=22 January 2020|access-date=22 January 2020}}</ref> On January 27th, Sloan made national headlines after tweeting in response to fellow leadership candidate Richard D\u00e9carie his belief that being gay is a choice.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://globalnews.ca/news/6480512/mp-derek-sloan-controversial-tweet/|title=Newly-elected Conservative MP Derek Sloan faces criticism after posting controversial tweet}}</ref> Sloan went on to say that \"L-G-B-T-Q is a Liberal term\" and argue that the science of whether sexual orientation is a choice is unclear during an interview on the CTV Power Panel.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ctvnews.ca/politics/science-doesn-t-confirm-biological-component-to-being-gay-tory-leadership-hopeful-says-1.4789014|title=Science doesn't confirm 'biological' component to being gay, Tory leadership hopeful says}}</ref> Sloan's comments were criticized by his former election campaign manager, Eric Lorenzen, and fellow leadership candidate Marilyn Gladu.\n\nA self-identified [[Social conservatism|social conservative]], Sloan has attracted controversy for the policy positions he has endorsed throughout the leadership race.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/politics/derek-sloan-conservative-leadership-1.5436227|title=Social conservative MP Derek Sloan running for Conservative leadership, promises 'bold ideas'}}</ref> Sloan has stated that were he elected leader he would permit Conservative MPs to reopen the abortion debate or introduce private member bills aimed at over-turning same sex marriage.<ref>{{cite web|title=EXCLUSIVE: Conservative leadership contender would let Canadian politicians debate abortion|url=https://www.lifesitenews.com/news/exclusive-conservative-leadership-contender-would-let-canadian-politicians-debate-abortion|date=February 11, 2020|publisher=Life Site|accessdate=April 11, 2020}}</ref> He also voiced opposition to Bill C-16, which protects people from discrimination on the basis of gender identity, thereby protecting the human rights of transgender individuals.<ref>{{cite web|title=Tory leadership hopeful supports conversion therapy for trans kids in car-crash TV interview|url=https://www.pinknews.co.uk/2020/03/30/canada-tory-conservative-leadership-derek-sloan-conversion-therapy-trans/|date=April 4, 2020|publisher=Pink News|accessdate=April 11, 2020}}</ref> He also vowed to vote against a federal ban on the pseudo-scientific practice of [[Conversion therapy|conversion therapy]], arguing that parents should be able to make children identify with the body they are born with.<ref>{{cite web|title=Tory leadership hopeful Sloan blasts Trudeau \u2018conversion therapy\u2019 ban as \u2018madness\u2019|url=https://www.lifesitenews.com/news/tory-leadership-hopeful-sloan-blasts-trudeau-conversion-therapy-ban-as-madness|date=April 4, 2020|publisher=Life Site|accessdate=April 11, 2020}}</ref> Sloan has been widely criticized in the media and even within the Conservative Party for these anti-LGBTQ views.<ref>{{cite web|title=Being gay is not a choice but who cares if it is?|url=https://www.thestar.com/opinion/star-columnists/2020/01/29/being-gay-is-not-a-choice-but-who-cares-if-it-is.html|date=April 4, 2020|publisher=Toronto Star|accessdate=April 11, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn February 6th, 2020, members of the [[Mohawks of the Bay of Quinte]] blockaded the [[Canadian National Railway]] north of [[Tyendinaga Mohawk Territory|Tyendinaga]], in support the Wet\u02bcsuwet\u02bcen hereditary chiefs' [[2020 Canadian pipeline and railway protests|opposition to the Coastal GasLink Pipeline.]] The blockade fell within Sloan's riding of [[Hastings\u2014Lennox and Addington]]. Sloan was criticized by his riding constituents for not taking time away from his leadership campaign to help end the blockade,<ref>{{cite web|title=Local MP says Liberals too slow in responding to rail blockades|url=https://www.facebook.com/InQuinte/posts/hastings-lennox-and-addington-mp-derek-sloan-says-the-federal-government-shouldn/2642807052454372/|date=February 18, 2020|publisher=In Quinte News|accessdate=April 16, 2020}}</ref> instead spending the second week of February campaigning in [[Toronto]].<ref>{{cite web|title=I had a great time meeting with the Filipino Community in Toronto recently!|url=https://twitter.com/DerekSloanCPC/status/1228748095401451520|date=February 15, 2020|publisher=@DerekSloanCPC on Twitter|accessdate=April 16, 2020}}</ref> Sloan spoke publicly about the blockade for the first time on February 18th, stating the Liberal government should have responded faster to the protests.<ref>{{cite web|title=Local MP says Liberals too slow in responding to rail blockades|url=https://inquinte.ca/story/local-mp-says-liberals-too-slow-in-responding-to-rail-blockades/direct?fbclid=IwAR0QMgdzEzPh8rm-TNjT-k9ItZ5vGPTgZwsmB1B0qXznFDS8Lw_j2iq94T8|date=February 18, 2020|publisher=In Quinte News|accessdate=April 16, 2020}}</ref> Three days later Sloan stated that while he had not met with the protesters, they were \"extremists,\" and he called on the [[Ontario Provincial Police|OPP]] to enforce an injunction against them.<ref>{{cite web|title=Sloan calls for OPP to remove Wyman Road blockade|url=https://inquinte.ca/story/sloan-calls-for-opp-to-remove-wyman-road-blockade|date=February 21, 2020|publisher=In Quinte News|accessdate=April 16, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Electoral record==\n\n{{Canadian election result/top|CA|2019|percent=yes|change=yes|expenditures=yes|prelim=no}}\n{{CANelec|CA|Conservative|[[Derek Sloan]]|21,968|41.4|-0.5||}}\n{{CANelec|CA|Liberal|[[Mike Bossio]]|19,721|37.1|-5.3||}}\n{{CANelec|CA|NDP|David Tough|6,984|13.2|+0.5||}}\n{{CANelec|CA|Green|Sari Watson|3,114|5.9|+3.0||}}\n{{CANelec|CA|PPC|Adam L. E. Gray|1,307|2.5||}}\n{{Canadian election result/total|Total valid votes/Expense limit|53,094|100.0 || }}\n{{Canadian election result/total|Total rejected ballots|352||}}\n{{Canadian election result/total|Turnout|53,446|66.7|}}\n{{Canadian election result/total|Eligible voters|80,079}}\n{{CANelec/source|Source: [[Elections Canada]]<ref>{{cite web |title=List of confirmed candidates |url=https://www.elections.ca/content2.aspx?section=can&dir=cand/lst&document=index&lang=e |website=Elections Canada |accessdate=October 3, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Election Night Results |url=https://enr.elections.ca/ElectoralDistricts.aspx?lang=e |publisher=Elections Canada |accessdate=October 31, 2019}}</ref>}}\n{{end}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n==External links==\n* {{Canadian Parliament links|ID=20111}}\n{{Current Members of the Canadian House of Commons}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Sloan, Derek}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Canadian Seventh-day Adventists]]\n[[Category:Conservative Party of Canada MPs]]\n[[Category:Members of the House of Commons of Canada from Ontario]]\n[[Category:1984 births]]\n[[Category:Lawyers in Ontario]]\n", "text_old": "{{pp-semi|small=yes}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific-prefix = \n| name             =Derek Sloan\n| honorific-suffix = {{post-nominals|country=CAN|MP|size=100%}}\n| image            = Dereksloan2110.jpg\n| imagesize        = \n| riding           = [[Hastings\u2014Lennox and Addington]]\n| parliament       = Canadian\n| term_start       = October 21, 2019\n| term_end         =\n| predecessor      =[[Mike Bossio]]\n| successor        =\n| birth_date       = {{Birth date and age|1984|11|11}}\n| birth_place      = [[Norfolk County, Ontario]], Canada\n| death_date       =\n| death_place      =\n| profession       = Lawyer\n| party            = [[Conservative Party of Canada|Conservative]]\n| residence        = \n| footnotes        = \n| spouse           = \n| children= \n|}}\n\n'''Derek Sloan''' {{post-nominals|country=CAN|MP}} (born November 11, 1984) is a [[Canadians|Canadian]] politician who was elected to represent the [[electoral district (Canada)|riding]] of [[Hastings\u2014Lennox and Addington]] in the [[House of Commons of Canada]] in the [[2019 Canadian federal election]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Canada election results: Hastings-Lennox and Addington|url=https://globalnews.ca/news/5760824/canada-election-hastings-lennox-and-addington/|date=October 21, 2019|publisher=Global News|accessdate=October 21, 2019}}</ref> He is the first [[Seventh-day Adventist Church|Seventh-day Adventist]] ever elected to the [[Canadian House of Commons]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Interview With Derek Sloan, First Adventist Elected to Canada\u2019s Parliament|url=https://www.nadadventist.org/news/interview-derek-sloan-first-adventist-elected-canadas-parliament|date=December 11, 2019|publisher=North American Division of the Seventh-day Adventist Church|accessdate=December 18, 2019}}</ref> Sloan is running as a candidate for the [[2020 Conservative Party of Canada leadership election|leadership of the Conservative Party of Canada]], and has gained notoriety for his anti-LGBTQ views.<ref>{{cite web|title=Being gay is not a choice but who cares if it is?|url=https://www.thestar.com/opinion/star-columnists/2020/01/29/being-gay-is-not-a-choice-but-who-cares-if-it-is.html|date=April 4, 2020|publisher=Toronto Star|accessdate=April 11, 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Background ==\nSloan was born in 1984 and raised near [[Waterford, Ontario|Waterford]] in Ontario.<ref>{{cite web|title=Team Member: Derek Sloan|url=https://www.conservative.ca/team-member/derek-sloan/|date=August 12, 2018|publisher=Conservative Party of Canada|accessdate=April 11, 2020}}</ref> He attended [[Kingsway College]], a private [[Seventh-day Adventist]] highschool in [[Oshawa]].<ref>{{cite journal |title=Congratulations |journal=KC Contact |date=Spring 2014 |page=14 |url=https://static1.squarespace.com/static/58af1200f7e0ab64d5e083d0/t/59808c5620099ecf2e5c7041/1501596794725/KC%2BContact%2BSpring%2B2014%2BEdition.pdf |accessdate=27 December 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn 2003, Sloan enrolled at [[Pacific Union College|Pacific Union College (PUC)]], a private university in [[Napa Valley AVA|Napa Valley]], [[California]] associated with the [[Seventh-day Adventist Church]]. There he completed a bachelor degree in business in 2007.<ref>{{cite web|title=Candidates: Derek Sloan|url=https://www.insideottawavalley.com/ottawavalley-news/federal-election/vote-2019/candidates/17212|date=October 20, 2019|publisher=InsideOttawaValley.com|accessdate=April 11, 2020}}</ref> While attending PUC, Sloan served as President of the university's Student Association in 2007.<ref>{{cite web|title=Candidates: Derek Sloan|url=https://www.insideottawavalley.com/ottawavalley-news/federal-election/vote-2019/candidates/17212|date=October 20, 2019|publisher=InsideOttawaValley.com|accessdate=April 11, 2020}}</ref>\n\nAfter graduating, Sloan moved to [[Toronto|Toronto, Ontario]] to work at a water-fuel systems company.<ref>{{cite web|title=325 PUC graduates celebrate with faith, flying tortillas|url=https://napavalleyregister.com/community/star/news/local/puc-graduates-celebrate-with-faith-flying-tortillas/article_29488f5e-3382-5351-b75f-01cee2e27a33.html|date=June 21, 2007|publisher=Napa Valley Register|accessdate=April 11, 2020}}</ref> Then, between 2011 and 2014 he ran Sloan's Furniture Liquidation in [[Oshawa]]. In 2014, Sloan began a law degree at [[Queen's University at Kingston|Queen's University]] in [[Kingston, Ontario]], and he finished articling in 2018. Sloan has said he pursued law because he was interested in \"defending religious liberties against political correctness.\"<ref>{{cite web|title=INTERVIEW WITH DEREK SLOAN, FIRST ADVENTIST ELECTED TO CANADA\u2019S PARLIAMENT|url=https://news.eud.adventist.org/en/all-news/news/go/2019-12-12/interview-with-derek-sloan-first-adventist-elected-to-canadas-parliament/|date=December 12, 2019|publisher=Seventh-day Adventist Church|accessdate=April 11, 2020}}</ref>\n\nSloan is married to his wife Jennifer, and they have two daughters, Fiona and Nora, and a son Callum.<ref>{{cite web|title=Team Member: Derek Sloan|url=https://www.conservative.ca/team-member/derek-sloan/|date=August 12, 2018|publisher=Conservative Party of Canada|accessdate=April 11, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Political Career==\n\n===2019 Federal Election===\nIn 2018, Sloan announced that he would seek the [[Conservative Party of Canada]] nomination for the riding of [[Hastings\u2014Lennox and Addington]], despite having only recently moved to the riding.<ref>{{cite web|title=Four candidates for HL&A Conservative race|url=https://www.quintenews.com/2018/11/14/4-candidates-in-the-conservative-race-for-hla/|date=November 14, 2018|publisher=Quinte News|accessdate=April 11, 2020}}</ref> At the nomination meeting, Sloan defeated three other candidates: a City Councillor who had served for fifteen years in [[Belleville, Ontario|Belleville]], a lawyer who had lived in the area for twenty years, and a local business owner.<ref>{{cite web|title=Sloan selected as new Conservative candidate in federal election|url=https://inquinte.ca/story/sloan-selected-as-new-conservative-candidate-in-federal-election|date=November 14, 2018|publisher=In Quinte News|accessdate=December 8, 2018}}</ref> Sloan would go on to defeat [[Liberal Party of Canada|Liberal]] incumbent [[Mike Bossio]] in the [[2019 Canadian Federal Election|2019 Federal Election]].\n\n===2020 Conservative Party Leadership Election===\nSloan announced his candidacy for the [[2020 Conservative Party of Canada leadership election]] on 22 January 2020.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/DerekSloanCPC/status/1220012199042670592?ref_src=twsrc%5Etfw%7Ctwcamp%5Etweetembed%7Ctwterm%5E1220022905045749766&ref_url=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.ctvnews.ca%2Fpolitics%2Frookie-mp-derek-sloan-says-he-s-running-for-conservative-leadership-1.4778567|title=I'm in. It's time to stop being afraid to be conservative. Stay tuned...|first=Derek|last=Sloan|date=22 January 2020|access-date=22 January 2020}}</ref> On January 27th, Sloan made national headlines after tweeting in response to fellow leadership candidate Richard D\u00e9carie his belief that being gay is a choice.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://globalnews.ca/news/6480512/mp-derek-sloan-controversial-tweet/|title=Newly-elected Conservative MP Derek Sloan faces criticism after posting controversial tweet}}</ref> Sloan went on to say that \"L-G-B-T-Q is a Liberal term\" and argue that the science of whether sexual orientation is a choice is unclear during an interview on the CTV Power Panel.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ctvnews.ca/politics/science-doesn-t-confirm-biological-component-to-being-gay-tory-leadership-hopeful-says-1.4789014|title=Science doesn't confirm 'biological' component to being gay, Tory leadership hopeful says}}</ref> Sloan's comments were criticized by his former election campaign manager, Eric Lorenzen, and fellow leadership candidate Marilyn Gladu.\n\nA self-identified [[Social conservatism|social conservative]], Sloan has attracted controversy for the policy positions he has endorsed throughout the leadership race.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/politics/derek-sloan-conservative-leadership-1.5436227|title=Social conservative MP Derek Sloan running for Conservative leadership, promises 'bold ideas'}}</ref> Sloan has stated that were he elected leader he would permit Conservative MPs to reopen the abortion debate or introduce private member bills aimed at over-turning same sex marriage.<ref>{{cite web|title=EXCLUSIVE: Conservative leadership contender would let Canadian politicians debate abortion|url=https://www.lifesitenews.com/news/exclusive-conservative-leadership-contender-would-let-canadian-politicians-debate-abortion|date=February 11, 2020|publisher=Life Site|accessdate=April 11, 2020}}</ref> He also voiced opposition to Bill C-16, which protects people from discrimination on the basis of gender identity, thereby protecting the human rights of transgender individuals.<ref>{{cite web|title=Tory leadership hopeful supports conversion therapy for trans kids in car-crash TV interview|url=https://www.pinknews.co.uk/2020/03/30/canada-tory-conservative-leadership-derek-sloan-conversion-therapy-trans/|date=April 4, 2020|publisher=Pink News|accessdate=April 11, 2020}}</ref> He also vowed to vote against a federal ban on the pseudo-scientific practice of [[Conversion therapy|conversion therapy]], arguing that parents should be able to make children identify with the body they are born with.<ref>{{cite web|title=Tory leadership hopeful Sloan blasts Trudeau \u2018conversion therapy\u2019 ban as \u2018madness\u2019|url=https://www.lifesitenews.com/news/tory-leadership-hopeful-sloan-blasts-trudeau-conversion-therapy-ban-as-madness|date=April 4, 2020|publisher=Life Site|accessdate=April 11, 2020}}</ref> Sloan has been widely criticized in the media and even within the Conservative Party for these anti-LGBTQ views.<ref>{{cite web|title=Being gay is not a choice but who cares if it is?|url=https://www.thestar.com/opinion/star-columnists/2020/01/29/being-gay-is-not-a-choice-but-who-cares-if-it-is.html|date=April 4, 2020|publisher=Toronto Star|accessdate=April 11, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn February 6th, 2020, members of the [[Mohawks of the Bay of Quinte]] blockaded the [[Canadian National Railway]] north of [[Tyendinaga Mohawk Territory|Tyendinaga]], in support the Wet\u02bcsuwet\u02bcen hereditary chiefs' [[2020 Canadian pipeline and railway protests|opposition to the Coastal GasLink Pipeline.]] The blockade fell within Sloan's riding of [[Hastings\u2014Lennox and Addington]]. Sloan was criticized by his riding constituents for not taking time away from his leadership campaign to help end the blockade,<ref>{{cite web|title=Local MP says Liberals too slow in responding to rail blockades|url=https://www.facebook.com/InQuinte/posts/hastings-lennox-and-addington-mp-derek-sloan-says-the-federal-government-shouldn/2642807052454372/|date=February 18, 2020|publisher=In Quinte News|accessdate=April 16, 2020}}</ref> instead spending the second week of February campaigning in [[Toronto]].<ref>{{cite web|title=I had a great time meeting with the Filipino Community in Toronto recently!|url=https://twitter.com/DerekSloanCPC/status/1228748095401451520|date=February 15, 2020|publisher=@DerekSloanCPC on Twitter|accessdate=April 16, 2020}}</ref> Sloan spoke publicly about the blockade for the first time on February 18th, stating the Liberal government should have responded faster to the protests.<ref>{{cite web|title=Local MP says Liberals too slow in responding to rail blockades|url=https://inquinte.ca/story/local-mp-says-liberals-too-slow-in-responding-to-rail-blockades/direct?fbclid=IwAR0QMgdzEzPh8rm-TNjT-k9ItZ5vGPTgZwsmB1B0qXznFDS8Lw_j2iq94T8|date=February 18, 2020|publisher=In Quinte News|accessdate=April 16, 2020}}</ref> Three days later Sloan stated that while he had not met with the protesters, they were \"extremists,\" and he called on the [[Ontario Provincial Police|OPP]] to enforce an injunction against them.<ref>{{cite web|title=Sloan calls for OPP to remove Wyman Road blockade|url=https://inquinte.ca/story/sloan-calls-for-opp-to-remove-wyman-road-blockade|date=February 21, 2020|publisher=In Quinte News|accessdate=April 16, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Electoral record==\n\n{{Canadian election result/top|CA|2019|percent=yes|change=yes|expenditures=yes|prelim=no}}\n{{CANelec|CA|Conservative|[[Derek Sloan]]|21,968|41.4|-0.5||}}\n{{CANelec|CA|Liberal|[[Mike Bossio]]|19,721|37.1|-5.3||}}\n{{CANelec|CA|NDP|David Tough|6,984|13.2|+0.5||}}\n{{CANelec|CA|Green|Sari Watson|3,114|5.9|+3.0||}}\n{{CANelec|CA|PPC|Adam L. E. Gray|1,307|2.5||}}\n{{Canadian election result/total|Total valid votes/Expense limit|53,094|100.0 || }}\n{{Canadian election result/total|Total rejected ballots|352||}}\n{{Canadian election result/total|Turnout|53,446|66.7|}}\n{{Canadian election result/total|Eligible voters|80,079}}\n{{CANelec/source|Source: [[Elections Canada]]<ref>{{cite web |title=List of confirmed candidates |url=https://www.elections.ca/content2.aspx?section=can&dir=cand/lst&document=index&lang=e |website=Elections Canada |accessdate=October 3, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Election Night Results |url=https://enr.elections.ca/ElectoralDistricts.aspx?lang=e |publisher=Elections Canada |accessdate=October 31, 2019}}</ref>}}\n{{end}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n==External links==\n* {{Canadian Parliament links|ID=20111}}\n{{Current Members of the Canadian House of Commons}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Sloan, Derek}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Canadian Seventh-day Adventists]]\n[[Category:Conservative Party of Canada MPs]]\n[[Category:Members of the House of Commons of Canada from Ontario]]\n[[Category:1984 births]]\n[[Category:Lawyers in Ontario]]\n", "name_user": "Ymblanter", "label": "vandal", "comment": "(added pp-semi)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Derek_Sloan"}
{"title_page": "List of Westworld characters", "text_new": "{{short description|Wikipedia list article}}\n{{about|the television series|the main characters of the film|Westworld (film)}}\n{{DISPLAYTITLE:List of ''Westworld'' characters}}\n[[File:WestworldLogo.png|right|220px]]\n''[[Westworld (TV series)|Westworld]]'' is an American [[science fiction]] [[Western (genre)|western]] [[thriller (genre)|thriller]] [[Television program|television series]], based on the [[Westworld (film)|1973 film of the same name]]. The series takes place in the fictional Westworld, a technologically advanced Western-themed amusement park which is populated by androids, which are called \"hosts\", while its human visitors are known as \"guests\".\n\nThe series features an ensemble cast, including [[Evan Rachel Wood]], [[Thandie Newton]], [[Jeffrey Wright]], [[James Marsden]], [[Ingrid Bols\u00f8 Berdal]], [[Luke Hemsworth]], [[Sidse Babett Knudsen]], [[Simon Quarterman]], [[Rodrigo Santoro]], [[Angela Sarafyan]], [[Shannon Woodward]], [[Ed Harris]], [[Anthony Hopkins]], [[Ben Barnes (actor)|Ben Barnes]], [[Clifton Collins Jr.]], [[Jimmi Simpson]], and [[Tessa Thompson]]. Joining in the main cast in the second season are [[Louis Herthum]] and [[Talulah Riley]], both of whom recurred in the first season, and new cast members [[Fares Fares]], [[Gustaf Skarsg\u00e5rd]], [[Katja Herbers]], and [[Zahn McClarnon]]. [[Aaron Paul]] and [[Vincent Cassel]] join the main cast in the third season.\n\n==Appearances==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center; width:auto\"\n|-\"\n! rowspan=\"2\" | Actor\n! rowspan=\"2\" | Character\n! colspan=\"3\" | Seasons\n|-\n! style=\"width:100px;\" | [[Westworld (season 1)|1]]\n! style=\"width:100px;\" | [[Westworld (season 2)|2]]\n! style=\"width:100px;\" | [[Westworld (season 3)|3]]\n|-\n! colspan=\"5\" | [[#Main characters|Main cast]]\n|-\n| [[Evan Rachel Wood]] || [[#Dolores Abernathy|Dolores Abernathy]] || colspan=\"3\" {{CMain}}\n|-\n| [[Thandie Newton]] || [[#Maeve Millay|Maeve Millay]] || colspan=\"3\" {{CMain|Main}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" | [[Jeffrey Wright (actor)|Jeffrey Wright]] || [[#Bernard Lowe|Bernard Lowe]] || colspan=\"3\" {{CMain|Main}}\n|-\n| [[#Arnold Weber|Arnold Weber]] || colspan=\"2\" {{CMain|Main}} || {{N/A|}}\n|-\n| [[James Marsden]] || [[#Teddy Flood|Teddy Flood]] || colspan=\"2\" {{CMain|Main}} || {{N/A|}}\n|-\n| [[Ingrid Bols\u00f8 Berdal]] || [[#Armistice|Armistice]] || colspan=\"2\" {{CMain|Main}}{{efn|name=appearcredit|Credited with the main cast in the episodes in which they appear.}} || {{N/A|}}\n|-\n| [[Luke Hemsworth]] || [[#Ashley Stubbs|Ashley Stubbs]] || colspan=\"3\" {{CMain|Main}}{{efn|name=appearcredit}}\n|-\n| [[Sidse Babett Knudsen]] || [[#Theresa Cullen|Theresa Cullen]] || {{CMain|Main}}{{efn|name=appearcredit}} || {{TableTBA|[[Stock footage|Archive]]}} || {{N/A|}}\n|-\n| [[Simon Quarterman]] || [[#Lee Sizemore|Lee Sizemore]]{{efn|In season 3, Simon Quarterman portrays a digital replica of Lee Sizemore in a simulation.}} || colspan=\"3\" {{CMain|Main}}{{efn|name=appearcredit}}\n|-\n| [[Rodrigo Santoro]] || [[#Hector Escaton|Hector Escaton]]{{efn|In season 3, Rodrigo Santoro portrays Ettore, a host character of Warworld, in a simulation.}} || colspan=\"2\" {{CMain|Main}}{{efn|name=appearcredit}} || {{CGuest}}\n|-\n| [[Angela Sarafyan]] || [[#Clementine Pennyfeather|Clementine Pennyfeather]] || colspan=\"2\" {{CMain|Main}}{{efn|name=appearcredit}} || {{N/A|}}\n|-\n| [[Shannon Woodward]] || [[#Elsie Hughes|Elsie Hughes]] || colspan=\"2\" {{CMain|Main}}{{efn|name=appearcredit}} || {{N/A|}}\n|-\n| [[Ed Harris]]{{efn|Child William is portrayed by guest star Zayd Kiszonak in season 3.}} || [[#William|William \"Man in Black\"]] || colspan=\"3\" {{CMain|Main}}\n|-\n| [[Anthony Hopkins]]{{efn|Young Robert Ford is portrayed by co-star [[Paul Fox (actor)|Paul Fox]]<ref name=\"paulfox\">{{cite web|url=https://www.spotlight.com/interactive/cv/1/M50979.html|title=PAUL FOX|website=Spotlight|accessdate=22 June 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190622115717/https://www.spotlight.com/interactive/cv/1/M50979.html|archivedate=22 June 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> (Young Doctor) in season 1 and guest star Paul Riley Fox<ref name=\"paulRfox\">{{cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/name/nm0809538/|title=Paul Riley Fox|website=IMDb|accessdate=22 June 2019}}</ref> (Younger Man) in season 2<!--These are two different actors: see sources-->.}} || [[#Robert Ford|Robert Ford]]{{efn|In season 2, Anthony Hopkins also portrays a digital replica of Robert Ford.}} || {{CMain|Main}} || {{CMain|Main}}{{efn|Credited with the main cast in the episodes in which he appears, except for his uncredited [[Cameo appearance|cameos]] in \"[[Journey into Night]]\", \"[[Reunion (Westworld)|Reunion]]\", and \"[[Phase Space (Westworld)|Phase Space]]\".}} || {{N/A|}}\n|-\n| [[Ben Barnes (actor)|Ben Barnes]] || [[#Logan Delos|Logan Delos]]{{efn|In season 2, Ben Barnes also portrays The Forge.}} || {{CMain|Main}}{{efn|name=appearcredit}} || {{CRecurring}} || {{N/A|}}\n|-\n| [[Clifton Collins Jr.]] || [[#Lawrence Gonzales|Lawrence Gonzales]]{{efn|In season 1, Clifton Collins Jr. also portrays El Lazo, a host character of Westworld, in flashbacks.}} || colspan=\"2\" {{CMain|Main}}{{efn|name=appearcredit}} || {{N/A|}}\n|-\n| [[Jimmi Simpson]] || Young [[#William|William]] || {{CMain|Main}}{{efn|name=appearcredit}} || {{CRecurring|Recurring}} || {{CGuest|Guest}}\n|-\n| [[Tessa Thompson]] || [[#Charlotte Hale|Charlotte Hale]]{{efn|In seasons 2\u20133, Tessa Thompson also portrays Dolores Abernathy in a host replica of Charlotte Hale.}} || {{CMain|Main}}{{efn|name=appearcredit}} || colspan=\"2\" {{CMain|Main}}\n|-\n| [[Fares Fares]] || Antoine Costa || {{N/A|}} || {{CMain|Main}}{{efn|name=appearcredit}} || {{N/A|}}\n|-\n| [[Louis Herthum]] || [[#Peter Abernathy|Peter Abernathy]] || {{CRecurring|Recurring}} || {{CMain|Main}}{{efn|name=appearcredit}} || {{N/A|}}\n|-\n| [[Talulah Riley]] |