{"title_page": "Chorlton-on-Medlock", "text_new": "{{distinguish|Chorlton-cum-Hardy}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2019}}\n{{Infobox UK place\n|country =                 England\n|official_name=            Chorlton-on-Medlock\n|coordinates = {{coord|53.466667|-2.216667|display=inline,title}}\n|label_position = top\n|population=        \n|metropolitan_borough=    [[Manchester]]\n|metropolitan_county=     [[Greater Manchester]]\n|region=                  North West England\n|constituency_westminster=    [[Manchester Central (UK Parliament constituency)|Manchester Central]]\n|post_town=        MANCHESTER\n|postcode_district = M12,13\n|postcode_area= M\n|dial_code=      0161\n|os_grid_reference=     SJ856967\n|static_image= Chorlton-upon-Medlock Town Hall (3287955601).jpg\n|static_image_caption= The former town hall of Chorlton-on-Medlock \n|london_distance=\n}}\n\n'''Chorlton-on-Medlock''' is an [[inner city]] area of [[Manchester]], England.\n\n[[Historic counties of England|Historically]] in [[Lancashire]], Chorlton-on-Medlock is bordered to the north by the [[River Medlock]], which runs immediately south of [[Manchester city centre]]. Its other borders roughly correspond to Stockport Road, Hathersage Road, Moss Lane East and Boundary Lane. Neighbouring districts are [[Hulme]] to the west, [[Ardwick]] to the east and [[Victoria Park, Manchester|Victoria Park]], [[Rusholme]] and [[Moss Side]] to the south. A large portion of the district along [[Oxford Road, Manchester|Oxford Road]] is occupied by the campuses of the [[University of Manchester]], [[Manchester Metropolitan University]], and the [[Royal Northern College of Music]]. To the south of the university's Oxford Road campus a considerable area is occupied by a group of contiguous hospitals including [[Manchester Royal Infirmary]], to the west of which is [[Whitworth Park]].\n\n==History==\n{{further|History of Manchester}}\n[[File:Kro Bar, Manchester 1.jpg|upright|Kro Bar, 325 Oxford Road|thumb]]\n[[File:Student Health Centre, Chorlton-on-Medlock.jpg|thumb|upright|Waterloo Place, 176-188 Oxford Road]]\nIn [[medieval]] times, the district was known as Chorlton Row and was a [[township (England)|township]] of the [[Manchester (ancient parish)|ancient parish of Manchester]] in the [[Salford (hundred)|Salford Hundred]] of Lancashire. Towards the end of the 18th century, it developed as a residential suburb of Manchester and in the extreme north of the township a number of [[cotton mill]]s were established. In 1820 the parish church of [[All Saints' Day|All Saints]] was built. Development began in 1793\u201394 and most of the important streets were given impressive names, Oxford Street, Cambridge Street and Grosvenor Street.\n\nOver the following 30 years residential development spread southwards as far as Tuer Street: and by the mid-1840s to High Street. Few dwellings of that period remain today apart from Waterloo Place, 323, 325, 327 & 333 Oxford Road, and [[Grove House, Manchester|Grove House]] (316\u2013324).<ref>Hartwell (2001)</ref>\n\nIn 1830, the town hall on Cavendish Street was built to the designs of Richard Lane. On the creation of the [[municipal borough]] of Manchester [[History of Manchester#Industrial and cultural growth|in 1838]] the township was absorbed into the borough. At this time the southern area was still partly rural with some larger dwellings of wealthy people (e.g., [[John Owens (merchant)|John Owens]] in Nelson Street). After the Poor Law Reform of 1834 the district became part of the Chorlton [[Poor Law Union]] and the offices of the Board of Guardians were built in Cavendish Street (these are now the Ormond Building of the Metropolitan University). The arrival of Owens College in 1873 was the beginning of a different kind of development leading to the academic campus of today.\n\nThough most of the township was originally middle class in character by the early 20th century it was very much a working class district. The housing conditions were described in 1931 by the Manchester and District Social Survey Society.<ref>Housing Group of the St James', Birch, Fellowship (1931) ''Some Housing Conditions in Chorlton-on-Medlock, Manchester''.</ref>{{-}}\n\n==Geography==\n[[Image:ManchesterMetUni-AllSaintsBldg-20070421.jpg|thumb|The All Saints Building on the Manchester Campus of the Metropolitan University]]\n[[Image:Mancunian Way UMIST.jpg|thumb|A view of the Mancunian Way elevated motorway near what was [[UMIST]] campus]]\nThe [[M postcode area|M13 postcode district]] includes both [[Ardwick]] and Chorlton on Medlock, although the area east of Boundary Lane and west of the [[University Dental Hospital of Manchester|Dental Hospital]] has a [[Hulme]] (M15) postcode, and [[Greenheys, Manchester|Greenheys]] is now in [[Moss Side]] ward rather than Chorlton on Medlock. The River Medlock is the boundary with [[Manchester city centre]], which includes the Sackville Street campus of the [[University of Manchester#Campus and facilities|University of Manchester]] (or \"North Campus\" rather than \"South Campus\"). A large area of Chorlton on Medlock south-west of this is occupied by the [[Manchester Metropolitan University]].\n\n{{Geographic Location\n|title     = '''Neighbouring districts and places.'''\n|Northwest = [[Hulme]]\n|North     = [[Manchester|Manchester city centre]]\n|Northeast = [[Ardwick]]\n|West      = [[Hulme]]\n|Centre    = Chorlton-on-Medlock\n|East      = [[Gorton]]\n|Southwest = [[Moss Side]]\n|South     = [[Rusholme]]\n|Southeast = [[Rusholme]]\n}}\n\n==Transport==\n[[File:Manchester Upper Brook Street geograph-3392290-by-Ben-Brooksbank.jpg|thumb|Upper Brook Street]]\nChorlton on Medlock is crossed by the [[Mancunian Way]] (opened 1967), running west to east through its northern part. The main routes through the suburb to south Manchester are (west to east) Cambridge Street (leading to Higher Cambridge Street, Lloyd Street North and Upper Lloyd Street), Oxford Road (leading to [[Wilmslow Road]]; the busiest route, both for private and public transport), and Upper Brook Street (dual carriageway continuing from [[Princess Street, Manchester|Princess Street]] and leading to Anson Road).\n\n==Landmarks==\n[[Image:Royal Eye Hospital.jpg|thumb|Manchester Royal Eye Hospital, 1886\u20132009]]\n[[File:Chorlton New Mill - geograph.org.uk - 712931.jpg|Chorlton New Mill|thumb|left|upright]]\nThe front of the former Chorlton-upon-Medlock Town Hall can be seen at its original location on Cavendish Street at All Saints. The building, with its [[Doric order|Doric]] [[portico]], dates from 1830\u201331 and was designed by [[Richard Lane (architect)|Richard Lane]].<ref>Pevsner, ''The Buildings of England: South Lancashire''</ref> The original interior was removed and a new structure added to the rear in 1970. A red plaque on the building commemorates the Fifth [[Pan-African Congress]], which was held there from 15\u201321 October 1945. Decisions taken at that conference led to independence for a number of [[Africa]]n and [[Caribbean]] countries. In Nelson Street the former home of the [[Pankhurst]] family is now the [[Pankhurst Centre]]. The Ormond Building of the Manchester Metropolitan University was originally the home of the [[Chorlton Poor Law Union|Chorlton Union]] Board of Guardians (responsible under the 1834 [[Poor Law]] for most of what is now south Manchester). Next to the town hall building is the original building of the Manchester College of Art (1880\u201381: architect [[George T. Redmayne]]) in a [[Gothic revival]] style.\n\nFurther down Oxford Road are the University of Manchester (frontage built 1888\u20131902), the former [[Manchester Royal Eye Hospital]] (1886), [[Manchester Royal Infirmary]] (1908) and the [[Whitworth Art Gallery]] (1898\u20131908).\n\n==Religion==\n[[File:Upper Brook Street Chapel 9.jpg|thumb|[[Upper Brook Street Chapel, Manchester|Welsh Baptist Chapel]], Upper Brook Street]]\nThe parish church of All Saints (1820) and the earlier Church of St Luke (founded before 1804 but a new church was built by John Lowe in 1865; part of Old Chorlton Hall was used as the rectory)<ref name=\"auto\">Fleetwood-Hesketh, Peter (1955) ''Murray's Lancashire Architectural Guide''. London: John Murray; p. 160</ref> (to the east) have been demolished as have several other [[Anglican church]]es in this area. Anglican churches which are disused include St Stephen's ([[Edwin Hugh Shellard|E. H. Shellard]], 1853), St Paul's (Clegg & Knowles, 1862), and St Ambrose (H. C. Charlewood, 1884):<ref name=\"auto\"/> these have all been demolished apart from St Ambrose which was used by the University of Manchester as an Islamic prayer room but  the prayer room is now elsewhere. In Greenheys there was formerly an Anglican church of St Clement on Denmark Road (architect Henry R. Price, 1881, decorated by John Lowe, 1886<ref name=\"auto\"/>).\n[[File:Brunswick Parish Church, Manchester.jpg|thumb|Brunswick Parish Church]]\n[[File:St Augustine's, Manchester.jpg|thumb|St Augustine's Catholic Church]]\nThe oldest [[Roman Catholic church]] in Chorlton-on-Medlock was the [[Church of the Holy Name of Jesus, Manchester|Church of the Holy Name]] on Oxford Road (built between 1869 and 1871), a fine example of the work of the architect [[Joseph Aloysius Hansom]]. St Augustine's, [[Sackville Street (Manchester)|Granby Row]] (demolished in 1908 to allow expansion at the [[UMIST|Municipal College of Technology]]) was replaced by a second St Augustine's in York Street, Chorlton-on-Medlock (ruined by German bombing in 1940 during World War II):<ref>York Street was until 1970 a street parallel to Oxford Road and running from the River Medlock to Rusholme Road (through the site afterwards used for New Broadcasting House, the BBC HQ).--Makepeace, Chris (1995) ''Looking Back at Hulme, Moss Side, Chorlton on Medlock & Ardwick''. Altrincham: Willow; pp. 14 & 20</ref> its successor is at Lower Ormond Street on the [[Manchester Metropolitan University]] campus in a building which serves also as a chaplaincy to the University. This church was built in dark brick to the designs of Desmond Williams & Associates in 1967\u201368.<ref>Hartwell, Clare; Hyde, Matthew & Pevsner, Nikolaus (2004) ''Lancashire: Manchester and the South-East''. New Haven: Yale University Press; p. 420</ref> It replaced an earlier church of the Holy Family which was at first a chapel-of-ease to St Augustine's, then an independent parish, but a chapel-of-ease again from 1908 to 1940 when it became the parish church of St Augustine's parish.<ref>[http://www.genuki.org.uk/big/eng/LAN/Manchester/StAugustine.shtml St Augustine Manchester--Roman Catholic]; Genuki (citing ''Salford Diocesan Almanac''; 2007)</ref>\n\nThe Armenian church in Upper Brook Street was the first purpose-built [[Armenian Catholic Church|Armenian church]] in Western Europe. It is dedicated to the Holy Trinity and opened at Easter 1870. The architects were Royle & Bennett, 1869\u201370, and they chose an eclectic neo-Gothic style. At the east end is a rounded apse and the interior is simple though the altar is elaborate.<ref>Hartwell (2004); pp. 421\u201322</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.armenianchurchmanchester.org/|title=The Holy Trinity Armenian Church of Manchester|year=2009|publisher=Holy Trinity Armenian Church|accessdate=14 December 2010}}</ref>\n\nThere were also many [[Nonconformist (Protestantism)|Nonconformist]] chapels (most of them now demolished) such as the Cavendish Street Congregational Church, Cavendish Street (architect [[Edward Walters]], 1847\u201348), the Union Chapel, Oxford Road and a [[Presbyterian]] chapel at All Saints. The chapel in Cavendish Street was a particularly fine [[Dissenting Gothic|neo-Gothic]] building but was demolished in the early 1970s to allow expansion by Manchester Polytechnic. It has replaced an earlier chapel in [[Mosley Street]]. The [[Upper Brook Street Chapel, Manchester|Welsh Baptist Chapel]], on Upper Brook Street, was designed in the early 19th century by [[Charles Barry|Sir Charles Barry]], who designed the [[Palace of Westminster]] shortly afterwards, and in Greenheys there was a [[Stephen Joseph Studio|German Protestant Church]] in Wright Street (ca. 1871).\n\nThe [[Salvation Army]]'s Manchester I corps is based at Manchester Temple, Grosvenor Street. It was founded in 1879 and a modern Salvation Army building stands on the site of the original one, and is called [[Manchester Central (Salvation Army)|Manchester Central]].\n\nThere are two mosques in Chorlton-on-Medlock, the Salimiya Mosque and the [[Islamic Academy of Manchester]], Upper Brook Street (in the building of the former Welsh Baptist Chapel). The former church of St Ambrose was used by the University of Manchester as an Islamic prayer room for several years. There are prayer rooms at the University of Manchester and at the Manchester Metropolitan University in Oxford Road.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mosquedirectory.co.uk/search_mosque/mosquesearch.php?mosque=Chorlton-on-Medlock|title=Mosque Search Chorlton-on-Medlock|first=Tahire Mehmood|last=Faruq|website=www.mosquedirectory.co.uk}}</ref>\n\n==Notable people==\nSee also [[List of people from Manchester]]\n[[Image:Gaskell.jpg|thumb|right|[[84 Plymouth Grove]], home of [[William Gaskell|William]] and [[Elizabeth Gaskell]], from 1850]]\n[[File:Swinton Grove Park - geograph.org.uk - 48151.jpg|thumb|right|Swinton Grove Park, near 84 Plymouth Grove]]\n[[File:Manchester Academy 1.jpg|thumb|right|Manchester Academy, south of [[Manchester University Students' Union]], Oxford Road]]\n[[File:The Salutation, Manchester.jpg|thumb|The Salutation public house in Higher Chatham Street]]\n[[File:Robert Angus Smith blue plaque .jpg|thumb|A [[Royal Society of Chemistry]] Blue plaque commemorating Smith in Grosvenor Square, the site of R. Angus Smith's laboratory]]\n'''''19th century'''''\n*[[William Worby Beaumont]] (1848\u20131929), automotive engineer and inventor\n*[[Maud Boyd]] (1867\u20131929), actress and operatic singer\n*[[Friedrich Engels]] (1820\u20131895), [[Germans|German]] [[social scientist]] and [[philosopher]], lived here for a time; the site of his lodging is commemorated by a plaque on Aberdeen House, Whitworth Park Halls of Residence.\n*[[John Owens (merchant)|John Owens]] the merchant (after whom [[Owens College]] was named) lived in Nelson Street.\n*[[Elizabeth Gaskell]] lived in a house at [[84, Plymouth Grove]] for the last 15 years of her life<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.elizabethgaskellhouse.org |title=Elizabeth Gaskell House, 84 Plymouth Grove}}</ref>\n*[[William Gaskell]], Nonconformist minister and writer, husband of Elizabeth Gaskell\n*[[Charles Hall\u00e9]], musician, lived at Greenheys for a time\n*[[Thomas De Quincey]], writer, also lived at Greenheys: he was born at Cross Street, Manchester\n*Walter Arthur Copinger, lawyer and scholar, lived in Greenheys<ref>{{cite web|url=http://homepage.ntlworld.com/brenda.scragg/MANCHESTER%20BOOK%20COLLECTORS.htm |title=Manchester book collectors |last=Scragg |first=Brenda J. |accessdate=2009-06-13 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20050212094529/http://homepage.ntlworld.com/brenda.scragg/MANCHESTER%20BOOK%20COLLECTORS.htm |archivedate=2005-02-12 }}</ref>\n*[[George Gissing]] 1857\u20131903, writer, lived on Grafton Street when he was a student at Owens College in 1876.\n*[[Samuel Mendel]] businessman, later built [[Manley Hall, Manchester|Manley Hall]].\n*[[Robert Angus Smith]], chemist, had his laboratory was in Grosvenor Square.\n\n'''''20th century'''''\n*[[James Bernard (elocutionist)|James Bernard]], reciter, elocutionist, author, born in Chorlton-on-Medlock in 1874\n*[[John Cassidy (artist)|John Cassidy]], sculptor, worked at a studio in Lincoln Grove, also lodged in the district\n*[[Catherine Chisholm]], GP and paediatrician: the first woman to study medicine at [[Manchester Medical School]], practised in Oxford Road<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mosi.org.uk/media/612328/dr%20catherine%20chisholm%20(large%20print).rtf|title=Catherine Chisholm|accessdate=2009-05-14|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071118164358/http://www.mosi.org.uk/media/612328/dr%20catherine%20chisholm%20%28large%20print%29.rtf|archivedate=2007-11-18}}</ref> and was medical officer of the [[Manchester High School for Girls]] in Dover Street, 1908\u201338<ref>''Manchester High School for Girls, 1874\u20131974''.</ref> She retired in 1948 having founded the [[Duchess of York Hospital|Manchester Babies' Hospital]] (afterwards the Duchess of York Hospital) in 1914. Originally this was in Chorlton-on-Medlock but soon moved to Levenshulme and then to Burnage.<ref>Mohr, Peter D. (2003) \"Dr Catherine Chisholm (1879\u20131952) of the Manchester Babies' Hospital\", in: ''Manchester Memoirs; vol. 140 (2001/02), pp. 21\u201330</ref>\n*[[David Lloyd George]], British [[Prime Minister]], was born here in 1863 but his family soon returned to Wales\n*[[Emmeline Pankhurst]], a founder of the British [[suffragette]] movement, lived in Nelson Street, Chorlton-on-Medlock, following her husband's death; the house is now the [[Pankhurst Centre]].\n*[[Eugene Halliday]] (1911\u20131987), artist, founder of the Institute for the Study of [[Sacred#Hierology|Hierological]] Values (now Eugene Halliday Society), lived as a child in Chorlton-on-Medlock. He studied at the Manchester School of Art in All Saints (see Landmarks above). A prolific writer, during the mid-1950s he wrote for the ''Cavendish Magazine'', published by the Congregational Chapel on Cavendish Street, Chorlton-on-Medlock (see Religion, above).\n*[[Arthur Delaney]] (1927\u20131987), artist, was born at 30 Clifford Street, Chorlton-on-Medlock. He was inspired by the work of [[L. S. Lowry]] and the memories of the happy years he spent as a boy in the Manchester of the 1930s with its smoke-laden skies, rattling trams and gas lamps.\n*[[Ellen Wilkinson]], Labour politician, Cabinet minister\n\n==See also==\n{{portal|Greater Manchester}}\n*[[Listed buildings in Manchester-M13]]\n*[[Listed buildings in Manchester-M15]]\n*[[New Broadcasting House (Manchester)]]\n\n==References==\n===Notes===\n{{Reflist}}\n\n===Bibliography===\n{{refbegin}}\n*{{cite book |first=Nikolaus |last=Pevsner |title=The Buildings of England: South Lancashire |publisher=Penguin |year=1969 |isbn=0-14-071036-1}}\n{{refend}}\n* Coates, Su (=S. D. F. Thomas) (1991) \"Manchester's German Gentlemen ... 1840\u20131920\". In: ''Manchester Region History Review''; vol. 5, no. 2, 1991/2\n* {{cite web|url=http://www.mancuniensis.info/ChorltonRowFP.htm |title=Account of Chorlton on Medlock in 1841}}\n*{{cite web|url=http://www.manchesterhomefinder.org/info/chorlton-on-medlock/chorlton-on-medlock.shtm |publisher=Manchester City Council |title=Description of Chorlton on Medlock |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090303154811/http://www.manchesterhomefinder.org/info/chorlton-on-medlock/chorlton-on-medlock.shtm |archivedate=March 3, 2009 }}\n\n==Further reading==\n*Kenyon, Margery ''Memories of Chorlton-on-Medlock''. Radcliffe: Neil Richardson {{ISBN|978-1-85216-179-8}} \n*Makepeace, Chris (1995) ''Looking Back at Hulme, Moss Side, Chorlton on Medlock & Ardwick''. Altrincham: Willow\n*Potts, Bob (1997) ''The Old Pubs of Hulme and Chorlton-on-Medlock''. Radcliffe: Neil Richardson\n\n{{Manchester}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Chorlton-On-Medlock}}\n[[Category:Areas of Manchester]]\n[[Category:Academic enclaves]]\n", "text_old": "{{distinguish|Chorlton-cum-Hardy}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2019}}\n{{Infobox UK place\n|country =                 England\n|official_name=            Chorlton-on-Medlock\n|coordinates = {{coord|53.466667|-2.216667|display=inline,title}}\n|label_position = top\n|population=        \n|metropolitan_borough=    [[Manchester]]\n|metropolitan_county=     [[Greater Manchester]]\n|region=                  North West England\n|constituency_westminster=    [[Manchester Central (UK Parliament constituency)|Manchester Central]]\n|post_town=        MANCHESTER\n|postcode_district = M12,13\n|postcode_area= M\n|dial_code=      0161\n|os_grid_reference=     SJ856967\n|static_image= Chorlton-upon-Medlock Town Hall (3287955601).jpg\n|static_image_caption= The former town hall of Chorlton-on-Medlock \n|london_distance=\n}}\n\n'''Chorlton-on-Medlock''' is an [[inner city]] area of [[Manchester]], England.\n\n[[Historic counties of England|Historically]] in [[Lancashire]], Chorlton-on-Medlock is bordered to the north by the [[River Medlock]], which runs immediately south of [[Manchester city centre]]. Its other borders roughly correspond to Stockport Road, Hathersage Road, Moss Lane East and Boundary Lane. Neighbouring districts are [[Hulme]] to the west, [[Ardwick]] to the east and [[Victoria Park, Manchester|Victoria Park]], [[Rusholme]] and [[Moss Side]] to the south. A large portion of the district along [[Oxford Road, Manchester|Oxford Road]] is occupied by the campuses of the [[University of Manchester]], [[Manchester Metropolitan University]], and the [[Royal Northern College of Music]]. To the south of the university's Oxford Road campus a considerable area is occupied by a group of contiguous hospitals including [[Manchester Royal Infirmary]], to the west of which is [[Whitworth Park]].\n\n==History==\n{{further|History of Manchester}}\n[[File:Kro Bar, Manchester 1.jpg|upright|Kro Bar, 325 Oxford Road|thumb]]\n[[File:Student Health Centre, Chorlton-on-Medlock.jpg|thumb|upright|Waterloo Place, 176-188 Oxford Road]]\nIn [[medieval]] times, the district was known as Chorlton Row and was a [[township (England)|township]] of the [[Manchester (ancient parish)|ancient parish of Manchester]] in the [[Salford (hundred)|Salford Hundred]] of Lancashire. Towards the end of the 18th century, it developed as a residential suburb of Manchester and in the extreme north of the township a number of [[cotton mill]]s were established. In 1820 the parish church of [[All Saints' Day|All Saints]] was built. Development began in 1793\u201394 and most of the important streets were given impressive names, Oxford Street, Cambridge Street and Grosvenor Street.\n\nOver the following 30 years residential development spread southwards as far as Tuer Street: and by the mid-1840s to High Street. Few dwellings of that period remain today apart from Waterloo Place, 323, 325, 327 & 333 Oxford Road, and [[Grove House, Manchester|Grove House]] (316\u2013324).<ref>Hartwell (2001)</ref>\n\nIn 1830, the town hall on Cavendish Street was built to the designs of Richard Lane. On the creation of the [[municipal borough]] of Manchester [[History of Manchester#Industrial and cultural growth|in 1838]] the township was absorbed into the borough. At this time the southern area was still partly rural with some larger dwellings of wealthy people (e.g., [[John Owens (merchant)|John Owens]] in Nelson Street). After the Poor Law Reform of 1834 the district became part of the Chorlton [[Poor Law Union]] and the offices of the Board of Guardians were built in Cavendish Street (these are now the Ormond Building of the Metropolitan University). The arrival of Owens College in 1873 was the beginning of a different kind of development leading to the academic campus of today.\n\nThough most of the township was originally middle class in character by the early 20th century it was very much a working class district. The housing conditions were described in 1931 by the Manchester and District Social Survey Society.<ref>Housing Group of the St James', Birch, Fellowship (1931) ''Some Housing Conditions in Chorlton-on-Medlock, Manchester''.</ref>{{-}}\n\n==Geography==\n[[Image:ManchesterMetUni-AllSaintsBldg-20070421.jpg|thumb|The All Saints Building on the Manchester Campus of the Metropolitan University]]\n[[Image:Mancunian Way UMIST.jpg|thumb|A view of the Mancunian Way elevated motorway near what was [[UMIST]] campus]]\nThe [[M postcode area|M13 postcode district]] includes both [[Ardwick]] and Chorlton on Medlock, although the area east of Boundary Lane and west of the [[University Dental Hospital of Manchester|Dental Hospital]] has a [[Hulme]] (M15) postcode, and [[Greenheys, Manchester|Greenheys]] is now in [[Moss Side]] ward rather than Chorlton on Medlock. The River Medlock is the boundary with [[Manchester city centre]], which includes the Sackville Street campus of the [[University of Manchester#Campus and facilities|University of Manchester]] (or \"North Campus\" rather than \"South Campus\"). A large area of Chorlton on Medlock south-west of this is occupied by the [[Manchester Metropolitan University]].\n\n{{Geographic Location\n|title     = '''Neighbouring districts and places.'''\n|Northwest = [[Hulme]]\n|North     = [[Manchester|Manchester city centre]]\n|Northeast = [[Ardwick]]\n|West      = [[Hulme]]\n|Centre    = Chorlton-on-Medlock\n|East      = [[Gorton]]\n|Southwest = [[Moss Side]]\n|South     = [[Rusholme]]\n|Southeast = [[Rusholme]]\n}}\n\n==Transport==\n[[File:Manchester Upper Brook Street geograph-3392290-by-Ben-Brooksbank.jpg|thumb|Upper Brook Street]]\nChorlton on Medlock is crossed by the [[Mancunian Way]] (opened 1967), running west to east through its northern part. The main routes through the suburb to south Manchester are (west to east) Cambridge Street (leading to Higher Cambridge Street, Lloyd Street North and Upper Lloyd Street), Oxford Road (leading to [[Wilmslow Road]]; the busiest route, both for private and public transport), and Upper Brook Street (dual carriageway continuing from [[Princess Street, Manchester|Princess Street]] and leading to Anson Road).\n\n==Landmarks==\n[[Image:Royal Eye Hospital.jpg|thumb|Manchester Royal Eye Hospital, 1886\u20132009]]\n[[File:Chorlton New Mill - geograph.org.uk - 712931.jpg|Chorlton New Mill|thumb|left|upright]]\nThe front of the former Chorlton-upon-Medlock Town Hall can be seen at its original location on Cavendish Street at All Saints. The building, with its [[Doric order|Doric]] [[portico]], dates from 1830\u201331 and was designed by [[Richard Lane (architect)|Richard Lane]].<ref>Pevsner, ''The Buildings of England: South Lancashire''</ref> The original interior was removed and a new structure added to the rear in 1970. A red plaque on the building commemorates the Fifth [[Pan-African Congress]], which was held there from 15\u201321 October 1945. Decisions taken at that conference led to independence for a number of [[Africa]]n and [[Caribbean]] countries. In Nelson Street the former home of the [[Pankhurst]] family is now the [[Pankhurst Centre]]. The Ormond Building of the Manchester Metropolitan University was originally the home of the [[Chorlton Poor Law Union|Chorlton Union]] Board of Guardians (responsible under the 1834 [[Poor Law]] for most of what is now south Manchester). Next to the town hall building is the original building of the Manchester College of Art (1880\u201381: architect [[George T. Redmayne]]) in a [[Gothic revival]] style.\n\nFurther down Oxford Road are the University of Manchester (frontage built 1888\u20131902), the former [[Manchester Royal Eye Hospital]] (1886), [[Manchester Royal Infirmary]] (1908) and the [[Whitworth Art Gallery]] (1898\u20131908).\n\n==Religion==\n[[File:Upper Brook Street Chapel 9.jpg|thumb|[[Upper Brook Street Chapel, Manchester|Welsh Baptist Chapel]], Upper Brook Street]]\nThe parish church of All Saints (1820) and the earlier Church of St Luke (founded before 1804 but a new church was built by John Lowe in 1865; part of Old Chorlton Hall was used as the rectory)<ref name=\"auto\">Fleetwood-Hesketh, Peter (1955) ''Murray's Lancashire Architectural Guide''. London: John Murray; p. 160</ref> (to the east) have been demolished as have several other [[Anglican church]]es in this area. Anglican churches which are disused include St Stephen's ([[Edwin Hugh Shellard|E. H. Shellard]], 1853), St Paul's (Clegg & Knowles, 1862), and St Ambrose (H. C. Charlewood, 1884):<ref name=\"auto\"/> these have all been demolished apart from St Ambrose which was used by the University of Manchester as an Islamic prayer room but  the prayer room is now elsewhere. In Greenheys there was formerly an Anglican church of St Clement on Denmark Road (architect Henry R. Price, 1881, decorated by John Lowe, 1886<ref name=\"auto\"/>).\n[[File:Brunswick Parish Church, Manchester.jpg|thumb|Brunswick Parish Church]]\n[[File:St Augustine's, Manchester.jpg|thumb|St Augustine's Catholic Church]]\nThe oldest [[Roman Catholic church]] in Chorlton-on-Medlock was the [[Church of the Holy Name of Jesus, Manchester|Church of the Holy Name]] on Oxford Road (built between 1869 and 1871), a fine example of the work of the architect [[Joseph Aloysius Hansom]]. St Augustine's, [[Sackville Street (Manchester)|Granby Row]] (demolished in 1908 to allow expansion at the [[UMIST|Municipal College of Technology]]) was replaced by a second St Augustine's in York Street, Chorlton-on-Medlock (ruined by German bombing in 1940 during World War II):<ref>York Street was until 1970 a street parallel to Oxford Road and running from the River Medlock to Rusholme Road (through the site afterwards used for New Broadcasting House, the BBC HQ).--Makepeace, Chris (1995) ''Looking Back at Hulme, Moss Side, Chorlton on Medlock & Ardwick''. Altrincham: Willow; pp. 14 & 20</ref> its successor is at Lower Ormond Street on the [[Manchester Metropolitan University]] campus in a building which serves also as a chaplaincy to the University. This church was built in dark brick to the designs of Desmond Williams & Associates in 1967\u201368.<ref>Hartwell, Clare; Hyde, Matthew & Pevsner, Nikolaus (2004) ''Lancashire: Manchester and the South-East''. New Haven: Yale University Press; p. 420</ref> It replaced an earlier church of the Holy Family which was at first a chapel-of-ease to St Augustine's, then an independent parish, but a chapel-of-ease again from 1908 to 1940 when it became the parish church of St Augustine's parish.<ref>[http://www.genuki.org.uk/big/eng/LAN/Manchester/StAugustine.shtml St Augustine Manchester--Roman Catholic]; Genuki (citing ''Salford Diocesan Almanac''; 2007)</ref>\n\nThe Armenian church in Upper Brook Street was the first purpose-built [[Armenian Catholic Church|Armenian church]] in Western Europe. It is dedicated to the Holy Trinity and opened at Easter 1870. The architects were Royle & Bennett, 1869\u201370, and they chose an eclectic neo-Gothic style. At the east end is a rounded apse and the interior is simple though the altar is elaborate.<ref>Hartwell (2004); pp. 421\u201322</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.armenianchurchmanchester.org/|title=The Holy Trinity Armenian Church of Manchester|year=2009|publisher=Holy Trinity Armenian Church|accessdate=14 December 2010}}</ref>\n\nThere were also many [[Nonconformist (Protestantism)|Nonconformist]] chapels (most of them now demolished) such as the Cavendish Street Congregational Church, Cavendish Street (architect [[Edward Walters]], 1847\u201348), the Union Chapel, Oxford Road and a [[Presbyterian]] chapel at All Saints. The chapel in Cavendish Street was a particularly fine [[Dissenting Gothic|neo-Gothic]] building but was demolished in the early 1970s to allow expansion by Manchester Polytechnic. It has replaced an earlier chapel in [[Mosley Street]]. The [[Upper Brook Street Chapel, Manchester|Welsh Baptist Chapel]], on Upper Brook Street, was designed in the early 19th century by [[Charles Barry|Sir Charles Barry]], who designed the [[Palace of Westminster]] shortly afterwards, and in Greenheys there was a [[Stephen Joseph Studio|German Protestant Church]] in Wright Street (ca. 1871).\n\nThe [[Salvation Army]]'s Manchester I corps is based at Manchester Temple, Grosvenor Street. It was founded in 1879 and a modern Salvation Army building stands on the site of the original one, and is called [[Manchester Central (Salvation Army)|Manchester Central]].\n\nThere are two mosques in Chorlton-on-Medlock, the Salimiya Mosque and the [[Islamic Academy of Manchester]], Upper Brook Street (in the building of the former Welsh Baptist Chapel). The former church of St Ambrose was used by the University of Manchester as an Islamic prayer room for several years. There are prayer rooms at the University of Manchester and at the Manchester Metropolitan University in Oxford Road.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mosquedirectory.co.uk/search_mosque/mosquesearch.php?mosque=Chorlton-on-Medlock|title=Mosque Search Chorlton-on-Medlock|first=Tahire Mehmood|last=Faruq|website=www.mosquedirectory.co.uk}}</ref>\n\n==Notable people==\nSee also [[List of people from Manchester]]\n[[File:Swinton Grove Park - geograph.org.uk - 48151.jpg|Swinton Grove Park (near 84 Plymouth Grove)|thumb]]\n[[Image:Gaskell.jpg|thumb|right|[[84 Plymouth Grove, Manchester|84 Plymouth Grove]], home of William and Elizabeth Gaskell from 1850]]\n[[File:Manchester Academy 1.jpg|thumb|right|Manchester Academy, south of Manchester University Students' Union, Oxford Road]]\n[[File:The Salutation, Manchester.jpg|thumb|The Salutation public house in Higher Chatham Street]]\n[[File:Robert Angus Smith blue plaque .jpg|thumb|A [[Royal Society of Chemistry]] Blue plaque commemorating Smith in Grosvenor Square, the site of R. Angus Smith's laboratory]]\n'''''19th century'''''\n*[[William Worby Beaumont]] (1848\u20131929), automotive engineer and inventor\n*[[Maud Boyd]] (1867-1929), actress and operatic singer\n*[[Friedrich Engels]], [[Germans|German]] [[social scientist]] and [[philosopher]], lived here for a time; the site of his lodging is commemorated by a plaque on Aberdeen House, Whitworth Park Halls of Residence.\n*[[John Owens (merchant)|John Owens]] the merchant (after whom [[Owens College]] was named) lived in Nelson Street.\n*[[Elizabeth Gaskell]] lived in a house at [[84, Plymouth Grove]] for the last 15 years of her life<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.elizabethgaskellhouse.org |title=Elizabeth Gaskell House, 84 Plymouth Grove}}</ref>\n*[[William Gaskell]], Nonconformist minister and writer, husband of Elizabeth Gaskell\n*[[Charles Hall\u00e9]], musician, lived at Greenheys for a time\n*[[Thomas De Quincey]], writer, also lived at Greenheys: he was born at Cross Street, Manchester\n*Walter Arthur Copinger, lawyer and scholar, lived in Greenheys<ref>{{cite web|url=http://homepage.ntlworld.com/brenda.scragg/MANCHESTER%20BOOK%20COLLECTORS.htm |title=Manchester book collectors |last=Scragg |first=Brenda J. |accessdate=2009-06-13 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20050212094529/http://homepage.ntlworld.com/brenda.scragg/MANCHESTER%20BOOK%20COLLECTORS.htm |archivedate=2005-02-12 }}</ref>\n*[[George Gissing]], writer, 1857-1903, lived in Grafton Street when he was a student at Owens College in 1876.\n*[[Samuel Mendel]] businessman, later built [[Manley Hall, Manchester|Manley Hall]].\n*[[Robert Angus Smith]], chemist; his laboratory was in Grosvenor Square.\n\n'''''20th century'''''\n*[[James Bernard (elocutionist)|James Bernard]], reciter, elocutionist, author, born in Chorlton-on-Medlock in 1874\n*[[John Cassidy (artist)|John Cassidy]], sculptor, worked at a studio in Lincoln Grove, also lodged in the district\n*[[Catherine Chisholm]], GP and paediatrician: the first woman to study medicine at [[Manchester Medical School]], practised in Oxford Road<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mosi.org.uk/media/612328/dr%20catherine%20chisholm%20(large%20print).rtf|title=Catherine Chisholm|accessdate=2009-05-14|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071118164358/http://www.mosi.org.uk/media/612328/dr%20catherine%20chisholm%20%28large%20print%29.rtf|archivedate=2007-11-18}}</ref> and was medical officer of the [[Manchester High School for Girls]] in Dover Street, 1908\u201338<ref>''Manchester High School for Girls, 1874\u20131974''.</ref> She retired in 1948 having founded the [[Duchess of York Hospital|Manchester Babies' Hospital]] (afterwards the Duchess of York Hospital) in 1914. Originally this was in Chorlton-on-Medlock but soon moved to Levenshulme and then to Burnage.<ref>Mohr, Peter D. (2003) \"Dr Catherine Chisholm (1879\u20131952) of the Manchester Babies' Hospital\", in: ''Manchester Memoirs; vol. 140 (2001/02), pp. 21\u201330</ref>\n*[[David Lloyd George]], British [[Prime Minister]], was born here in 1863 but his family soon returned to Wales\n*[[Emmeline Pankhurst]], a founder of the British [[suffragette]] movement, lived in Nelson Street, Chorlton-on-Medlock, following her husband's death; the house is now the [[Pankhurst Centre]].\n*[[Eugene Halliday]], artist, 1911\u20131987, founder of the Institute for the Study of [[Sacred#Hierology|Hierological]] Values (now Eugene Halliday Society), lived as a child in Chorlton-on-Medlock. He studied at the Manchester School of Art in All Saints (see Landmarks above). A prolific writer, during the mid-1950s he wrote for the ''Cavendish Magazine'', published by the Congregational Chapel on Cavendish Street, Chorlton-on-Medlock (see Religion, above).\n*[[Arthur Delaney]], artist, 1927\u20131987 was born at 30 Clifford Street, Chorlton-on-Medlock. He was inspired by the work of [[L. S. Lowry]] and the memories of the happy years he spent as a boy in the Manchester of the 1930s with its smoke-laden skies, rattling trams and gas lamps.\n*[[Ellen Wilkinson]], Labour politician, Cabinet minister\n\n==See also==\n{{portal|Greater Manchester}}\n*[[Listed buildings in Manchester-M13]]\n*[[Listed buildings in Manchester-M15]]\n*[[New Broadcasting House (Manchester)]]\n\n==References==\n===Notes===\n{{Reflist}}\n\n===Bibliography===\n{{refbegin}}\n*{{cite book |first=Nikolaus |last=Pevsner |title=The Buildings of England: South Lancashire |publisher=Penguin |year=1969 |isbn=0-14-071036-1}}\n{{refend}}\n* Coates, Su (=S. D. F. Thomas) (1991) \"Manchester's German Gentlemen ... 1840\u20131920\". In: ''Manchester Region History Review''; vol. 5, no. 2, 1991/2\n* {{cite web|url=http://www.mancuniensis.info/ChorltonRowFP.htm |title=Account of Chorlton on Medlock in 1841}}\n*{{cite web|url=http://www.manchesterhomefinder.org/info/chorlton-on-medlock/chorlton-on-medlock.shtm |publisher=Manchester City Council |title=Description of Chorlton on Medlock |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090303154811/http://www.manchesterhomefinder.org/info/chorlton-on-medlock/chorlton-on-medlock.shtm |archivedate=March 3, 2009 }}\n\n==Further reading==\n*Kenyon, Margery ''Memories of Chorlton-on-Medlock''. Radcliffe: Neil Richardson {{ISBN|978-1-85216-179-8}} \n*Makepeace, Chris (1995) ''Looking Back at Hulme, Moss Side, Chorlton on Medlock & Ardwick''. Altrincham: Willow\n*Potts, Bob (1997) ''The Old Pubs of Hulme and Chorlton-on-Medlock''. Radcliffe: Neil Richardson\n\n{{Manchester}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Chorlton-On-Medlock}}\n[[Category:Areas of Manchester]]\n[[Category:Academic enclaves]]\n", "name_user": "Martinevans123", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eNotable people:minor tweaks", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chorlton-on-Medlock"}
{"title_page": "Holly Rehder", "text_new": "[[File:Representative Holly Rehder.jpg|thumb]]\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name                = Holly Rehder\n| image               = \n| caption             = \n| office              = Member of the [[Missouri House of Representatives]] from the 148th district\n| term_start          = January 9, 2013\n| term_end            = \n| predecessor         = [[Ellen Brandom]]\n| successor           = \n| birth_name          = Holly Rene\u00e8 Thompson\n| birth_date          = {{Birth date and age|1969|9|15}}\n| birth_place         = [[Memphis, Tennessee]]\n| party               = [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]\n}}\n\n'''Holly Rehder''' (born September 15, 1969) is an American politician who has served in the [[Missouri House of Representatives]] from the 148th district since 2013.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://house.mo.gov/memberdetails.aspx?district=148&year=2017&code=R |title=Representative Holly Rehder |publisher=House.mo.gov |date= |accessdate=2018-08-22}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Benjamin Peters |url=https://themissouritimes.com/39288/close-personal-rep-holly-rehder/ |title=Up Close and Personal with Rep. Holly Rehder |publisher=The Missouri Times |date=2017-04-10 |accessdate=2018-08-22}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Missouri House of Representatives}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Rehder, Holly}}\n[[Category:1969 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Members of the Missouri House of Representatives]]\n[[Category:Missouri Republicans]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox officeholder\n|name         = Holly Rehder\n|image        = \n|caption      =\n|office       = Member of the [[Missouri House of Representatives]] from the 148th district\n|term_start   = January 9, 2013\n|term_end     = \n|predecessor  = [[Ellen Brandom]]\n|successor    = \n|birth_name   = \n|birth_date   = {{Birth date and age|1969|9|15}}\n|birth_place  = [[Memphis, Tennessee]]\n|party        = [[Republican Party (United States)|Republic